<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Rejects Proposal for Confederation of Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday rejected the
proposal made by Turkey and northern Cyprus concerning the
establishment of a confederation of two states on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
According to a joint communique issued after Monday's talks
between Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem and Turkish-Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash, the Greek-Cypriot and Turkish-Cypriot
communities on Cyprus should exist as two states under the
umbrella of a confederation, with Athens and Ankara acting as
respective security guarantors.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the proposal, Greek government spokesman Dimitris
Reppas said that the position adopted by Turkey and the
Turkish-Cypriots proves that Turkey's policy runs "completely
contrary" to the direction expected by the international community
and simply confirmed the provocativeness and aggressiveness
associated with the neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the international community to help seek ways of
resolving the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
If it was really interested in securing the conditions for a
settlement of the Cyprus issue, it should undertake initiative in
this direction, he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 the breakaway Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus recognized only by Turkey, against the
internationally acknowledged Republic of Cyprus dominated by the
Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
In 1960, Cyprus declared its independence from an 82-year
British colonial rule, and Greece, Turkey and Britain became the
three guarantors.
</P>
<P>
Believing the essence of the Cyprus problem remains a problem
of invasion and illegal occupation by Turkey, which currently
has more than 35,000 troops stationed in northern Cyprus, Greece
called on the international community to continue its efforts
towards a resumption of inter-communal dialogue on the divided
island and the commencement of a dialogue on reducing arms and the
island's demilitarization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
