<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 16:30 GMT, August 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- The Cambodian Constitutional Council rejected
opposition parties' poll complaints Monday, saying the complaints
were "baseless."
</P>
<P>
The rejection by the nation's highest legislative body paved
the way for the National Election Committee (NEC) to announce the
official election results.
</P>
<P>
The two main opposition parties -- the royalist FUNCINPEC party
led by Prince Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) of former
finance minister Sam Rainsy -- lodged 110 complaints to the
Constitutional Council. (Cambodia-Election Complaints)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl held separate telephone
conservations with U.S. President Bill Clinton, British Prime
Minister Tony Blair and Russian President Boris Yeltsin over the
weekend to discuss the current situation in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's spokesman Otto Hauser said that the chancellor expressed
in the telephone talks his "great concern" about the recent
development in Russia.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the stability of Russia and the continuation
of the political and economic reforms are of fundamental
importance for Europe and the world as a whole.
(Germany-Russia-Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ULAN BATOR -- Mongolian President Nachagyn Bagabandy on Monday
accepted the nomination of Renchinnyamin Amarjargal as the
country's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
A presidential spokesman said that Mongolia's National
Democratic Party nominated the 36-year-old Amarjargal, a Great
Hural member and acting minister of external relations, in a
letter to the president on August 28.
</P>
<P>
The president has agreed to the nomination and submitted it to
the Great Hural for approval, the spokesman said.
(Mongolia-PM-Nomination)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Acting Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin
said after his defeat in the State Duma voting on Monday that he
still plans to form a government, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"The country cannot go without a government," Chernomyrdin was
quoted by the Russian news agency as saying while leaving the
State Duma building after the voting on his nomination.
</P>
<P>
He will propose a cabinet line-up to President Boris Yeltsin on
Tuesday, he said. (Russia-Chernomyrdin-Cabinet)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian State Duma on Monday overwhelmingly voted
against President Boris Yeltsin's candidate for prime minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin after heated debates in the lower house of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Only 94 deputies voted for Chernomyrdin, way below the
required 226 votes from 450 lawmakers. Of the 345 deputies who
cast votes 251 voted against, with no abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The rejection would certainly push Russia into further
political stand-off between the Duma and Yeltsin, who is likely to
Chernomyrdin's candidacy. (Russia-Duma-Rejection) 
