<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Launch Water Projects in 25 Towns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Water
Resources of Ethiopia announced Monday that safe drinking water
development and rehabilitation projects will be launched in 25
towns across the country in this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Yohannes Gebre-Medhin, head of Drinking Water and Sewerage
Department of the ministry, told reporters that the survey and
design work to be carried out in the 25 towns will take 24
months.
</P>
<P>
Along side the survey and design work, rehabilitation and
expansion work of existing water facilities in these towns will
also be undertaken, said Yohannes.
</P>
<P>
He said that the survey and design work to be conducted will
envisage ways of increasing the water supply for the 25 towns in
the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
More than 65 million U.S. Dollars secured in loans from the
Ethiopian government and the World Bank has been allocated for
the execution of the projects, according to Yohannes.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia's current fiscal year started on July 8, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In Ethiopia, only about one-third population can get safe
drinking water and the government has put emphasis on increasing
safe water supply for more people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
