<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Promises to Free Captured Iranians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Taliban militia on
Monday promised to free all captured Iranians at an appropriate
time in order to build good relations with Iran, the official
Iranian news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Mullah Hassan Qalcheie, a close aide to the Taliban leader
Mulla Omar, told the IRNA in Dubai of the United Arab Emirates
that 11 Iranian diplomats and IRNA's reporter Mahmoud Saremi had
been safely transferred to a prison near Qandahar.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian diplomats were from the Iranian Consulate in Mazari
Sharif in northern Afghanistan, which was taken over by the Taliban
forces on August 8 from the hands of the Iranian-backed Northern
Alliance led by the ousted President Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that a senior Taliban official
has admitted the capture of the Iranian diplomats and reporter.
</P>
<P>
During the past three weeks, the Taliban has repeatedly denied
knowing the whereabouts of the group of Iranians, saying that
the Iranian Consulate in Mazari Sharif was evacuated when its
forces reached it.
</P>
<P>
However, Iran has been insisting that it has solid evidence to
prove that the Iranian diplomats and the IRNA reporter were in the
hands of the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Qalcheie said the Taliban would show its goodwill for
improvement of relations with Iran by freeing the captured
Iranians at an appropriate time.
</P>
<P>
He declined to say when the Iranian nationals would be freed,
adding that "the Taliban want good neighborly relations with the
Islamic Republic of Iran."
</P>
<P>
Although the Taliban forces have taken control over most of
Afghanistan, Iran refuses to recognize the Taliban government and
continues to support the Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
Tehran has warned that it would resort to "any means" to
secure the release of all captured Iranians.
</P>
<P>
To flex its military muscle, Iran's Islamic Revolutionary
Guards Corps have announced to hold a massive maneuver in the
northeastern province of Khorasan bordering Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
