<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Protests at DPRK's Missile Firing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Japan filed a protest Monday with
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) at its test
firing of a ballistic missile into the Pacific over Japan.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka said in a
statement that the Japanese government made the protest to a DPRK
deputy permanent representative at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the firing is extremely regrettable from
Japan's viewpoints on security, peace and stability in Northeast
Asia and non-proliferation of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi also said that
Japan would protest the firing to the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
"Once we find out about the details, we will probably make our
protest to Pyongyang in one form or other, notwithstanding the
lack of diplomatic relations," Obuchi told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK reportedly fired a ballistic missile Monday that
overflew northeastern Japan and fell into international waters in
the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Defense Agency officials said the missile had a cruising
range of 1,300 kilometers and the first stage rocket fell into the Sea
of Japan, adding that a warhead fell into the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK has not confirmed the test firing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
