<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Accuses Israel of Balking at U.S. Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
Monday accused Israel of balking at a U.S. proposal calling for
Israeli withdrawal from another 13.1 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is "still placing
hurdles in the way of the American proposal," Arafat told a press
conference jointly held with Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan after
their meeting here.
</P>
<P>
"We stick to the American proposal," Arafat said, adding that
the Palestinians remain committed to the peace process as "a
strategic option."
</P>
<P>
Hassan nodded in consent while Arafat was speaking.
</P>
<P>
But both refused to say whether they would accept the changes
to the proposal made by Netanyahu last week, under which Israel
pledges to hand over 10 percent of the West Bank to the
Palestinians but turn the rest into so-called "nature reserves"
where the Palestinians would have restricted powers.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have already accepted the widely-reported but
yet to be unveiled initiative, which was introduced by the U.S. in
January this year.
</P>
<P>
Israel has refrained from publicly endorsing it, citing
security concerns. But signs emerged recently that Israel has
decided to accept the U.S. initiative, provided that the
Palestinian side meet certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
Hassan reiterated Jordan's readiness to help the Palestinians
in their struggle to establish an independent state by using its
influence with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, the second Arab country to seal peace with Israel after
Egypt, has maintained warm relations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hassan is deputizing for King Hussein, who is in the U.S. for
cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Hassan, Arafat returned to the West Bank
city of Ramallah after the talks en route to South Africa to
attend summit of The Non-Aligned Movement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
