<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Not to Sign CTBT Under Coercion: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Monday declared
that it will not sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT)
under a coercive atmosphere caused by the economic sanctions of
the West.
</P>
<P>
In a foreign policy statement in the National Assembly,
Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Siddique Khan Kanju made it
clear that Islamabad "cannot sign the treaty, or for that matter,
accept any measure under duress or pressure."
</P>
<P>
"We alone will determine our course of action. We will maintain
the nuclear deterrence that we have already established," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said that "our voluntary moratorium and even accession to
CTBT, if we so decide in our national interest, will not erode our
nuclear deterrence capability."
</P>
<P>
He said that no country can contemplate aggression against
Pakistan. "However, our nuclear deterrent capability is meant for
peace and stability and not for conflict or war."
</P>
<P>
Islamabad, Kanju said, has delinked its position on CTBT from
that of India and declared that Pakistan would decide on the
treaty in the best interest of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
