<HEADLINE> French Football Star Launches Anti-Mine Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- French football star David
Ginola arrived here Monday afternoon to launch an anti-mine
campaign and to help those land mine victims in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The world-class star, accompanied by the delegate from the
International Commission of Red Cross (ICRC), told reporters that
"I want to bring hope to the Angolan children."
</P>
<P>
"I want to tell them," said Ginola, "with artificial limbs,
you still can take part in physical exercises and play football."
</P>
<P>
He hoped that during the three days of his stay here, he can
organize an international football match to raise fund for the
ICRC to help those land mine victims.
</P>
<P>
The football star pledged that he will exert his effort to
help end the disasters created by land mines.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had brought with him footballs and other
sports equipments and he had come here to show football skills to
the land mine victims. There are up to 150,000 people victimized
by various land mines scattered in the war-torn southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the British Princess Diana who was killed in a car
crash on August 31 last year, Ginola said that "the great cause
she was committed to should be carried on" and that the princess
had demonstrated the serious problem poised by the land mines.
</P>
<P>
The late princess was active in campaigning for the ban on the
use of lethal mines across the world. For this purpose, she paid
a visit from January 13 to 16, 1997, to Angola which is among the
countries having the most land mines in the world.
</P>
<P>
Ginola participated in various international games for 17
times representing France. 
</P>
