<HEADLINE> Uganda Supports Peace Solution to DRC Conflict: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Deputy Prime Minister
Eriya Kategaya said here Monday that his government supports
South African President Nelson Mandela's peace initiative in
regard to the on-going conflict in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Kategaya, who is here to participate in the 12th Non-Aligned
Movement summit, told a press conference that his country fully
supports cease-fire proposed by Mandela early this month.
</P>
<P>
He said if Uganda was called to defuse the conflict between
the DRC government troops of President Laurent Kabila and the
rebel forces, the Ugandan government would provide positive
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Kategaya, also foreign minister, accused the DRC government
troops of attacking Ugandan civilian people at the border between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"It must be guaranteed the 180-kilometer common border never
be used by bandits to attack civilian people," said Kategaya.
</P>
<P>
Referring to military support to the Kabila government given
by some member states of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC), Kategaya said that it was a mistake for
Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola to offer military support to Kabila
authorities.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the people of the DRC had never enjoyed their
legal right to vote since late dictator Mobutu Sese Seko took
power of former Zaire in 1965.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu was overthr by Kabila's troops in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Calling for general elections in the DRC, Kategaya stressed
that the rebel forces must be included in the future elections,
which, he said, is the only way to bring peace back to the
central African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
