<HEADLINE> 19 Ethiopians Flee Home from Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian government
spokeswoman said Monday that 19 Ethiopians have managed to return
home by escaping to Djibouti from Assab, Eritrea and traveling
for 10 days through scorching desert.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, Selome Taddesse, the spokeswoman
said that others who were with them did not survive the journey.
</P>
<P>
Selome said the 19 Ethiopians, one woman and 18 men, reached
the northern Djibouti town of Abok on August 22 and spent one
week recovering there before travelin to Djibouti Port.
</P>
<P>
They left Assab in three groups so as not to attract
attention, the spokeswoman said, quoting 30-year-old returnee
Girma Alemu Meko as saying that "there were seven of us to start
with but only two of us made it through the desert."
</P>
<P>
According to Selome, the 19 Ethiopians arrived in port of
Djibouti Saturday and then on Sunday they left for Ethiopia where
they first traveld to Dire Dawa, second largest city in
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Over 15,000 Ethiopians have returned home from Eritrea since
the border dispute between the two countries which erupted in May
this year, according to the office of the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Eritrea said that up to 17,000 of its nationals
have been expelled from Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
