<HEADLINE> Volkswagen Resumes Car Production in Sarajevo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Germany's largest carmaker
Volkswagen AG Monday reopened its factory in the Bosnian capital
city of Sarajevo where it was forced to leave during the Bosnian
civil war.
</P>
<P>
A Volkswagen spokesman said that the plant in Sarajevo is due
to have an initial output of 5,000 to 10,000 Skoda Felicia
vehicles a year.
</P>
<P>
If market conditions permitted, the production could be
expanded later to include other models, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
With the reopening of the Sarajevo plant, Volkswagen also
wanted to make contribution to stabilizing peace and prosperity in
the region, said Volkswagen chief Ferdinand Piech Monday at the
plant's opening ceremony in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel and Bosnian President
Alija Izetbegovic also attended the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The Volkswagen plant in Sarajevo was badly damaged during the
war by Serb forces. Volkswagen said it planned to put an
investment of about 50 million marks (28 million U.S. dollars) in
the new venture which the company will hold a 58 percent stake
while its Bosnian partner Unis Holding will have 42 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
