<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait exported 33.2 million Kuwait dinars
(109.56 million U.S. dollars) worth of non-oil products in the
first half of this year, official statistics said.
</P>
<P>
This showed a 27.2 percent rise compared with the exports of
the kind in the same period last year, the bi-annual newsletter
of the Kuwaiti Ministry of Trade and Commerce said.
</P>
<P>
The exports to Gulf Arab countries stood at 25.6 million dinars
(84.48 million dollars), 1.2 million dinars (3.96 million dollars)
higher than in the first six months of last year.
</P>
<P>
The country sold 740,128 dinars (2.44 million dollars) worth of
goods to other Arab countries compared with 614,724 dinars (2.02
million dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
The exports to non-Arab countries were 6.85 million dinars
(22.61 million dollars), 5.76 million dinars (19 million dollars)
more than in the first six months in 1997.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Kuwaiti cabinet has decided to grant a
priority to national firms 10 percent of the government contracts
and services.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued on Sunday said the decision is aimed at
boosting the participation of national firms in government
projects.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has asked the Ministry of Trade and Industry to
work out a mechanism for carrying out the decision.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Arabia has decided to link the power network of
Ha'el in the north of the kingdom with that in Kasim in the
central area, the Arabic daily Al-Hayat reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is estimated to cost 399.3 million Saudi
Arabia riyals (106.5 U.S. dollars), includes construction of a
220-kilometer-long grid to convey electricity.
</P>
<P>
The construction is expected to be implemented soon and
completed in two years' time.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Director General of the Syrian Public Organization
for Wire and Wireless Communications Makram Ebeid said the
government has decided to reduce the fees for phone calls between
Syria and Lebanon by 50 percent as of next month.
</P>
<P>
The fee for a digital phone call from Syria to Lebanon
currently stands at 35 Syria liras (0.7 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has cut down the fees for direct call to Syria by 45
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
