<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Rejects Denktash's Proposal for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' President Glafcos
Clerides Monday flatly rejected a proposal put forward by Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash for establishing a Cyprus
Confederation, the Cyprus News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement issued from South Africa, where he is
attending the Non-Aligned Movement summit, Clerides said the
intention behind Denktash's proposal was to render an independent
sovereign state into two protectorates, governed by unacceptable
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
He denounced Denktash's proposal as "new Turkish provocative
action" and urged the international community to respond directly
to it.
</P>
<P>
Denktash, speaking earlier Monday at a joint press conference
with visiting Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem in Turkish
Cypriot-controlled northern part of Nicosia, put forward a
five-point proposal on setting up a confederation of equal states
in order to end the 24-year-old division of the eastern
Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops took over the northern third in the wake of a failed
pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Denktash said the confederation he proposed was the "only
structure" that would safeguard the security, identity and well
being of the Greek and Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
But Clerides stressed that "under no circumstances can Mr
Denktash's proposal form a basis for talks as it is unacceptable
right from the start."
</P>
<P>
"It is also contrary to and contemptuous of the very
resolutions of the U.N. on Cyprus and the high-level agreements
which Mr. Denktash himself has signed," Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
He said the proposal also contravened "the substance and the
spirit of international law and all the international
organizations which have deplored the Turkish side's attempt to
question the independence and sovereignty of the Republic of
Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the National Council, a top advisory body to the
president on the the Cyprus problem, will be convened next Monday
to discuss its reaction to Denktash's action.
</P>
<P>
Greece, closest ally of the the Clerides-led Greek Cypriot
government, on Monday also rejected Denktash's proposal for the
establishment of a Cyprus Confederation.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Demetris Reppas was quoted as
saying in Athens that the proposal "reaffirms the provocative
and aggressive attitude our neighboring country (Turkey) has
adopted." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
