<HEADLINE> More Embassy Bombing Suspects to Be Sent to U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
arranged more suspects in the bomb attacks at U.S. embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania to be sent to New York later this week for
trail, federal law enforcement officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the FBI has issued a warning to U.S. corporations
with overseas offices to be on alert for possible terrorist
attacks against Americans, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Two suspects -- Mohamed Rashed Daoud al-Owhali and Mohamed
Sadeek Odeh -- were already sent last week from Kenya to New York
for trial.
</P>
<P>
The two suspects have been linked in court documents to exiled
Saudi millionaire Osama bin Laden, who was said to have
masterminded the two bombings at the U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania, which killed more than 260 people, including 12
Americans, and injured over 5,000.
</P>
<P>
The United States retaliated the bombings by firing cruise
missiles on Aug. 20 at a Sundanese pharmaceutical factory and
several targets in Afghanistan, both of which Washington alleged
were "terrorist-related" bases, funded by bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government has strongly denied the charges and
asked the United Nations to make a probe into the U.S. "criminal"
action.
</P>
<P>
One of the officials explained the FBI had issued alert warning
to U.S. corporations because "since the military strikes, the
potential for retaliation has existed."
</P>
<P>
"We are not aware of any specific threat, but we have received
relevant information," he said.
</P>
<P>
The FBI said in its alert warning, which was sent last
Thursday, that unnamed terrorists in Afghanistan allegedly were
offering bounties of "thousands of dollars" to other terrorist
groups to kill Americans in retaliation for the U.S. military
strikes on Sudan and Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
