<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Leaves for Moscow (updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
left here Monday for Moscow, where he is to meet Russian President
Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Clinton departed Andrews Air Force Base near Washington at 3:10
p.m. local time by Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
As both Clinton and Yeltsin have been wounded at home, analysts
believe that nothing substantial could be achieved during their
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The reason I'm going to Russia," Clinton said shortly before
leaving, "is because we have learned the hard way that problems
that develop beyond our borders sooner or later find their way to
our doorstep unless we help our friends and our neighbors."
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Yeltsin are to meet Tuesday and Wednesday for their
first full-scale summit since March 1997. Since then, they have
met briefly a few times, most recently in May, when both were in
Birmingham, England.
</P>
<P>
The two will focus on security and Russia's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said Russia can count on American support so long as it
stays the course to reform.
</P>
<P>
"If they will stay on the path of reform, to stabilize their
society and to strengthen their economy and to get growth back,
then I believe America and the rest of the Western nations with
strong economies should help them and indeed have an obligation to
help them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton offered two reasons for sticking with Russia: Russia
still has the second-largest nuclear arsenal in the world;
terrorists are trying to acquire weapons of mass destruction, and
without strong central control, Russian weaponry or know-how could
end up in the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will travel to Ireland and the British province of
Northern Ireland after his trip to Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
