<HEADLINE> Northwest Extends Flight Cancellation Due to Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Northwest Airlines
extended another day of its flight cancellations Monday and will
keep adding a day for each day of the strike as there was no sign
of resuming talks with the striking pilot union.
</P>
<P>
Domestic flights are now canceled through Wednesday and
international flights through Thursday, according to the company.
Even a settlement is reached, the fourth largest U.S. airline said
it would need two to three days to resume operations.
</P>
<P>
About 6,200 pilots represented by the Air Line Pilots
Association struck early Saturday after two years of negotiations
failed to resolve their wage and job security issues.
</P>
<P>
The strike affected thousands of passengers travelling although
the airline has helped passengers rebook on other airlines.
</P>
<P>
The airlines averaged about 1,700 flights that takes about
150,000 passengers a day. It carries about 80 percent of the
passengers in its hub airports in Minneapolis/St. Paul, Memphis
and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
The strike, the first by Northwest's pilots in 20 years, costs
the company 27 million U.S. dollars in loss of revenue each day.
</P>
<P>
The strike is the worst work stoppage at a major airline since
Eastern Airlines was brought to a halt in 1989. A strike by
American Airlines last year was halted by U.S. President Bill
Clinton soon after it started, but the White House said Clinton
will not intervene in the Northwest strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
