<HEADLINE> Mobilization of Aid for China's Flood Areas under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- International aid for
flood victims in China has amounted to over 5.7 million U.S.
dollars and mobilization of more aid is under way, it was
announced here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In its 7th report issued on Monday on the flood situation in
China and mobilization of aid resources for the Asian country, the
U.N. Office for Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) said a
U.N. team will be deployed in China shortly.
</P>
<P>
The team will carry out on-site assessment in some of the
worst-affected provinces and assist in the mobilization of
resources from the international community.
</P>
<P>
Detailed plans for this mission are currently being drawn up in
coordination with the U.N. Resident Coordinator in Beijing, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Losses to China caused by the worst flooding in 44 years have
been put at over 20 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Floods Since July along the Yangze River and in Northeast China
have killed more than 3,000 among the 240 million people affected.
</P>
<P>
The natural disaster has destroyed 5 million houses, inundated
21 million ha of lands and made 13.8 million homeless.
</P>
<P>
By August 27, the seventh crest was gathering on the Yangze
River, while the third flood peak on the swollen Songhua River was
still passing through the industrial heartlands.
</P>
<P>
Floods on the Nenjiang River have swamped more than 1,200 oil
wells in Daqing oil field, with 527 of them stopping production.
</P>
<P>
Preparations are also under way to combat potential disasters
on the Yellow River.  
</P>
</TEXT>
