<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Evidence To Theory of Snowball Earth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Scientists at Harvard
University and the University of Maryland have found new evidence
supporting a controversial theory that Earth was completely
covered in ice during a series of extreme glacial periods about
700 million years ago that almost completely snuffed out life on
the planet, according to the latest Science.
</P>
<P>
Paul F. Hoffman of Harvard university and colleagues studied
rock dating back between about 750 million years ago from what
is now Namibia in southwest Africa. Based on the composition of
the rock, the researchers conclude Earth experienced four deep
ice ages, each of which lasted millions of years.
</P>
<P>
The most likely explanation for this "collapse" would be
"global glaciation", the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult to imagine any other mechanism that would
shut down productivity on that scale other than global
glaciation," Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
No one knows why this would have occurred, but the
researchers speculate that this icy period may have ended when
volcanic activity caused the globe to warm again, allowing
whatever life that survived to begin to flourish again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
