<HEADLINE> Police Blows Up Suspicious Parcels Near NAM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Zhao Yi)
</P>
<P>
DURBAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- South African police bomb squad
Monday blew up two suspected parcels in controlled explosions in
central Durban where the 12th Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) summit
has been held since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The two pieces of suspicious parcels, found in two different
streets not far away from the conference site, were later proved
to have only contained clothing, sand and cement, police
spokesman Vishnu Naidoo told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Naidoo said that police received at least six telephone calls
Monday about suspicious parcels and bomb threats.
</P>
<P>
One of anonymous calls warning of bomb explosions was
apparently made by a woman, he added.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of policemen, military troops and security guards
were reportedly mobilized and deployed around the International
Conference Center, which has been provided for the six-day summit
since last weekend.
</P>
<P>
The ruling African National Congress (ANC) and the South
African Communist Party (SACP) have condemned the spate of bomb
threats.
</P>
<P>
The ANC said in a statement that unscrupulous elements were
attempting to divert the attention of the world from the agenda
of the NAM summit.
</P>
<P>
The SACP described the bomb threats as the work of
undemocratic elements trying to intimidate delegates and
undermine the struggle of the developing world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
