<HEADLINE> U.S. Closes Embassy in Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The United States government has
announced the indefinite closure of its embassy in Accra and all
other official installations in Ghana with effect from Monday,
following "increased threats to its installations," a report from
Accra said.
</P>
<P>
The embassy said in a statement that similar threats have been
received regarding U.S. installations in Togo.
</P>
<P>
It advised the public to stay clear of all official American
facilities unless it is absolutely necessary.
</P>
<P>
The embassy will offer services in emergency cases, it added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania were bombed on August
7, resulting in the death of over 250 people with more than 5,000
others injured.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with a local radio station, Bruce Leliof,
information officer at the U.S. embassy in Accra, said that the
American installations in Accra and Lome are likely to remain
closed until Wednesday, when the situation might be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
He said that the threats "in our view are credible enough and
we do not want to risk the lives of our nationals or Ghanaians
working or visiting us for any reason."
</P>
<P>
"All U.S. installations at the moment are out of bounds," he
said. "The closure has nothing to do with Ghana-U.S. relations or
with Africa-American relations. Terrorism has no limits and
strikes sometimes at unexpected places." 
</P>
</TEXT>
