<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Fun Can Also Go to Security Council Chair  (by Gu Zhenqiu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Monday usually stands for
the beginning of a working day in a week. But Monday of this week,
which falls on August 31, will see the exit of Danilo Turk as the
president of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
His news briefing, if not the last, turned to be an easy one,
as his humorous remarks were greeted with smiling faces and
laughters from his journalistic audience.
</P>
<P>
"Talking to you (reporters) at the end of the month is much
easier than the beginning of the month," Turk said here a few
hours before his end of the monthly rotating presidency.
</P>
<P>
It is "an interesting thing" to look at the U.N. Security
Council from the position of the president, and it is different
from what one can see simply from the seat of a council member,
Turk said.
</P>
<P>
The other interesting thing is "to watch body language on the
table," the outgoing council president said.
</P>
<P>
"It really helps, and you can sense what people really feel
about a thing" by watching their body language, Turk, the Security
Council president in August, told reporters only a few hours
before he leaves the presidency.
</P>
<P>
For an example, "people show their will to agree by encouraging
the president, not using words, but using their body language,"
Turk, Slovenian permanent representative to the United Nations,
said, "so you can see a lot of encouragement coming by the way
people look at you and by the way they move their hands."
</P>
<P>
"After all, the Security Council is rather a small forum,
(with) 15 members plus their advisors, who sometimes have a lot of
fun with what they hear from their bosses," he said.
</P>
<P>
On what surprised him the most in the passing month, Turk said,
"All you can see in the consultation room, the wish to come to
consensus is relatively strong, and that helps a lot if you have
to chair such meetings."
</P>
<P>
He said that it helps a lot if Security Council members are
willing to work on consensus.
</P>
<P>
"He is so charming and handsome," a female correspondent
commented before leaving the press conference hall in the U.N.
building.
</P>
<P>
Before he hands over the presidency to his successor, Turk is
expected to announce on Monday afternoon a presidential statement
on the situation of the Democratic Republic of Congo, which has
been plunged into a civil war since early this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
