<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Relax Control on Hard Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The National Bank of
Ethiopia announced Monday that commercial and private banks have
taken over the responsibility to issue import and export trade
license save for coffee, in addition to the management of hard
currency allocation and revenue administration.
</P>
<P>
Teklewold Atinafu, governor of the National Bank of Ethiopia,
told Ethiopian journalists here that commercial banks are allowed
as of Monday to buy and sell hard currency according to market
prices.
</P>
<P>
Teklewold said a foreign exchange auction, at which commercial
banks, licensed investors and organizations will take part for a
purchase to be effected with over 500,000 U.S. Dollars, will be
launched on September 5, 1998.
</P>
<P>
These measures taken by the Ethiopian government are aimed at
relaxing control on hard currency in a bid to promote foreign
trade in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency quoted the governor as saying that
measures taken include liberalizing centralized allocation of
hard currency and overcoming administrative procedures regarding
revenue and foreign trade current account payments in hard
currency.
</P>
<P>
Teklewold said, a directive was issued allowing exporters to
deposit in their account 10 percent of the hard currency they
earn and use it at their discretion.
</P>
<P>
He said that businessmen were also granted the right to change
90 percent of the hard currency with the local tender in a period
of four weeks.
</P>
<P>
The new measures also allowed expatriates residing in Ethiopia
to send abroad hard currency of the equivalent to their net
salaries.
</P>
<P>
According to the governor, the economic reform in the
financial sector were made in line with agreements reached
between the Ethiopian government and the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The measures which will boost the country's capacity to earn
more hard currency are testimonies to its commitment to adhering
to the principles of the free market economy, the governor added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
