<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Suffer Big Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrials
suffered their second-biggest point loss ever Monday, amid news of
a parliamentary showdown in Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Dow blue-chip industrial index lost 512.61 points to close
at 7,539.07. It was just under the memorable loss of October 19,
1987. It lost more than 6 percent on the day, wiping out all of
its gains for the year and nearly 20 percent below its all-time
closing high last July 17 of 9,337.97. The Dow ended 1997 at
7,908.25.
</P>
<P>
In Russia, the Boris Yeltsin's choice for prime minister was
disapproved in the parliament, despite Russia's growing economic
crisis. It was reported that President Clinton left Washington for
a summit meeting with President Boris Yeltsin to talk about
"reforms".
</P>
<P>
Russian and Japanese economic troubles have shaken Wall Street,
prompting fears of lower corporate profits and a global economic
slowdown.
</P>
<P>
Even large-company, well-known stocks were hit hard. They
included drugs, consumer goods and retailers. Technology stocks
led the major indexes lower, with Compaq, America Online and
Lucent the top-volume losers on the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 68.23 to 958.91.
</P>
<P>
The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index plunged 140.53
points to 1,499.15.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by more than 7 to 1 on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume reached 914.7 million,
as agains 838.75 million on the Friday session.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index declined 31.52 to 480.60, while the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 37.51 to 565.07.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies dropped 20.59 to
337.95.  
</P>
</TEXT>
