<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Call For Wetlands Protection (1) by Yin Huidi, Nie Xiaoyang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Heavy flooding along China's
Yangtze, Nenjiang and Songhua rivers have been caused, at least
in part, by the continuing degeneration of wetlands resulting from
reclamation.
</P>
<P>
The assertion was made by 80 experts on the Special Committee
of Wetland Ecology under the Chinese Society of Ecology in an open
letter issued today.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that the exploitation of wetlands along rivers
should be immediately prohibited. Efforts should be made to
strengthen education related to the functions and to enhance
public awareness of the need for expanded protection of the
natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Wetlands, the natural ecological systems often referred to as
the earth's "kidneys", play an extremely important role in water
conservation and the prevention of erosion and flooding.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the State Forestry Administration, Ministry of
Water Resources, State General Administration of Environmental
Protection and the Chinese Academy of Sciences, as well as related
colleges, universities and institutes, point out that the
increasing population and economic development have also
contributed to the continued deterioration of wetlands.
</P>
<P>
"The reclamation of lakes has led to the loss of 32.5 billion
cu.m. of storage capacity nationwide, with said figure equalling
one and a half of the storage capacity for the Three Gorges Dam
Project, the world's largest water conservation project currently
under construction," according to the experts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Authorities Call for Frugal Economic Practices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The General Office of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and the General
Office of the State Council today issued a circular calling for
frugal economic practices during the ongoing flood control and
relief effort.
</P>
<P>
The circular urged governments and departments at all levels to
practice thrift and eliminate waste in order to make greater
contributions to the nation's economic developments and capacity
to help more flood victims resume normal lives at the earliest
possible date.
</P>
<P>
"Flood victims urgently need large sums of money to rebuild
their homes and the entire nation is working around the clock to
realize the eight percent growth target for gross domestic product
(GDP). Public funds should not be squandered on costly
recreational activities," said the circular.
</P>
<P>
The circular prohibited government institutions from
constructing new office buildings, purchasing expensive
automobiles or mobile phones, and holding meetings in popular
tourism areas.
</P>
<P>
"Government officials should visit grass roots units and help
flood victims solve real problems, and no institution or
individual will be allowed to misappropriate relief funds," said
the circular. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Call For Wetlands Protection (2) by Yin Huidi, Nie Xiaoyang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
They added that the storage capacity for Poyang Lake, China's
largest freshwater lake, has dropped by 4.52 billion cu.m., or a
volume equal to a major flood diversion area along the Yangtze
River. The storage capacity for Dongting Lake, the nation's second
largest freshwater lake, has been reduced by 40 percent, while the
capacities for Honghu Lake and a large number of other lakes in
the middle reaches of the Yangtze River have dropped by as much as
50 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Related activities have, to a large extent, increased the
severity of flooding," according to the experts.
</P>
<P>
The silting rate in Dongting Lake has reached 75 percent and
the lake bed has continued to rise by 3.7 millimeters annually,
with the silting rate for Poyang Lake standing at 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
The letter indicates that numerous residential areas and
factories can be found in major flood diversion areas along the
Yangtze. Disruptions in the natural functions of many wetlands
along the Yangtze have greater pressure on the mainstream of the
river.
</P>
<P>
"Similar problems can be found along the Nenjiang and
Songhua rivers," according to the experts.
</P>
<P>
"Silting has also raised riverbeds and the construction of dams
has disrupted the hydrological patterns of lakes, rivers and
wetlands which have in turn increased flow rates and the frequency
of floods," according to the letter.
</P>
<P>
The experts pointed out that China is formulating a plan for
action concerning wetlands protection. Experts appealed for "the
implementation of the plan at the earliest possible date, and for
greater stress on the research and protection of wetlands."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
