<HEADLINE> Greece: Proposal for Confederation on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Greece Tuesday condemned the
idea of a confederation of two states on Cyprus proposed by Turkey
and the Turkish Cypriots, saying that this was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Tuesday by the Greek Foreign Ministry,
spokesman Theodoros Theodorou said that the idea was an indication
that the Turkish side continued to insist on extreme positions.
</P>
<P>
He said that Greece rejected the proposal because it continued
to reject U.N. Security Council resolutions on the Cyprus issue
for talks as a basis for the settlement of the protracted Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, which was raised Monday by Turkish Foreign
Minister Ismail Cem and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, was
anticipating the outcome of any talks, with the Turkish proposal
being presented as an ultimatum, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the development was a clear attempt by the
Turkish side to succeed in having northern Cyprus recognized and
to undermine Cyprus' entry into the European Union.
</P>
<P>
According to the proposal, the Greek Cypriot and Turkish
Cypriot communities on Cyprus should exist as two states under the
umbrella of a confederation, with Athens and Ankara acting as
respective security guarantors.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek-Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
