<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Goes Up to Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. construction
spending rose 0.4 percent in July to a record high, the Commerce
Department reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A big increase in residential building more than offset
commercial declines and essentially flat government outlays which
brought total construction spending to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 650.4 billion U.S. dollars, according to the
department.
</P>
<P>
Demand for new homes has been particularly strong this year as
plentiful jobs have boosted family incomes. Construction spending
is also being spurred by low interest rates and competition among
banks eager to finance real estate investment.
</P>
<P>
Residential construction spending rose 1.4 percent in July to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 296.3 billion dollars. Spending
rose on construction of single-family homes and remodeling, but
was flat for apartments.
</P>
<P>
The spending on commercial construction projects in July
dropped 1.2 percent to 166.2 billion dollars. Declines in spending
on factories and offices more than offset increases in other
areas, including hotels and shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
Government construction spending held relatively stable in
July, rising a tiny 0.07 percent to 145.4 billion dollars.
Spending increased on sewer and water supply systems, hospitals,
military facilities and other public buildings such as prisons,
police and fire stations and courthouses. But construction of
schools and highways and streets dipped. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
