<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Call For Wetlands Protection (1) by Yin Huidi, Nie Xiaoyang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Heavy flooding along China's
Yangtze, Nenjiang, and Songhua rivers have been caused, at least
in part, by the continuing degeneration of wetlands resulting from
reclamation.
</P>
<P>
The assertion was made by 80 experts on the Special Committee
of Wetland Ecology under the Chinese Society of Ecology in an open
letter issued today.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that the exploitation of wetlands along rivers
should be immediately prohibited. Efforts should be made to
strengthen education related to the functions and value of
wetlands and to enhance public awareness of the need for expanded
protection of the natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Wetlands, the natural ecological systems often referred to as
the earth's "kidneys", play an extremely important role in water
conservation and the prevention of erosion and flooding.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the State Forestry Administration, Ministry of
Water Resources, State General Administration of Environmental
Protection and the Chinese Academy of Sciences, as well as related
colleges, universities and institutes, point out that the
increasing population and economic development have also
contributed to the continued deterioration of wetlands.
</P>
<P>
"The reclamation of lakes has led to the loss of 32.5 billion
cu.m. of storage capacity nationwide, with said figure equalling
half of the storage capacity for the Three Gorges Dam Project, the
world's largest water conservation project currently under
construction," according to the experts.
</P>
<P>
They added that the storage capacity for Poyang Lake, China's
largest freshwater lake, has dropped by 452 million cu.m., or a
volume equal to a major flood diversion area along the Yangtze
River. The storage capacity for Dongting Lake, the nation's second
largest lake, has been reduced by 40 percent, while the capacities
for Honghu Lake and a large number of lakes in the middle reaches
of the Yangtze River have dropped by as much as 50 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
