<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Opposition Loses Control of Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korean opposition the
Grand National Party (GNP) Tuesday lost its control of the
National Assembly, or parliament, as three members defected to the
ruling camp.
</P>
<P>
The defection helped the ruling camp, the National Congress for
New Politics and the United Liberal Democrats respectively led by
President Kim Dae-jung and Prime Minister Kim Jong-pil, increase
its seats to 147 in the 299-member parliament.
</P>
<P>
It reduced the number of the opposition's seats in the
unicameral National Assembly from 150 to 147.
</P>
<P>
The defection is believed to have dealt a heavy blow to Lee
Hoi-chang, who won the GNP presidency over three other competitors
at the party national convention Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dae-jung, who has repeatedly accused the GNP of preventing
his reform bills from passing through the National Assembly since
he took office in February, has vowed to forge a majority by
recruiting opposition lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
The parliament, paralyzed for more than five months, resumed
operations last month after the opposition ended its parliamentary
boycott to vote on Kim Dae-jung's appointment of Kim Jong-pil as
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary dispute frustrated the government's drive to
tide over economic crisis caused by corporate failures and bad
loans of financial institutions late last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
