<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Reaffirms Significance of Three Gorges Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, today
affirmed the necessity for the Three Gorges Dam Project and
stressed the hydropower project will play a major role in reducing
floods by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
Li exchanged views with hydrologists and experts concerning
accelerated efforts to construct more water conservancy projects
following this year's wide-spread flooding.
</P>
<P>
This summer's devastating floods along the Yangtze River, and
the Nenjiang and Songhua rivers in northeastern China, have killed
an estimated 3,000 people and caused economic losses of well over
166 billion yuan (20.7 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Li said the law on flood control promulgated last year stresses
the establishment of a comprehensive flood prevention network of
reservoirs and dams for storing and discharging flood waters, as
well as for reinforcing river embankments and levees, and
constructing additional water and soil conservation projects.
</P>
<P>
He said detailed rules and regulations related to the law
should be introduced at the earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
Experts praised this year's flood control efforts and call for
increased investments in water conservancy projects.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Guangdou, a professor at Qinghua University, said it is
unrealistic to attempt to control floods along Yangtze River by
simply raising the heights of levees and reinforcing related
structure. He said diverting flood waters at the proper locations
and appropriate time would be both workable and effective.
</P>
<P>
Lin Bingnan, an academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences,
expressed his disagreement with certain people's assertions that
silting in rivers has raised water levels and was a major factor
in this year's catastrophic flooding.
</P>
<P>
Data gathered over the past 40-odd years fails to indicate a
tendency for the Yangtze riverbed to rise or fall, said Lin,
adding that silting affects some sections, but is far from a
common phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
A number of the experts tabled suggestions for future flood
prevention and control programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
