<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-Stricken Northeast China Areas Face Threat of Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The basically stable situation
concerning epidemic control in flooded areas throughout northeast
China continuous to face mounting danger from a possible major
outbreak of epidemics, according to the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
A ministry investigation team recently reported a 51.78 jump in
reported cases of infectious diseases in northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province over the same period last year. The majority
of cases involved typhoid fever and dysentery.
</P>
<P>
Reports for neighboring Jilin Province show a 14.4 percent
decline in reported cases compared with the same period of 1997,
with only 82 cases of typhoid and 317 cases of hemorrhagic fever.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the high population density and poor
sanitary conditions in temporary enclaves of flood victims, as
well as other factors such as the arrival of cold weather in
northeast China, will increase possibilities for an outbreak of
infectious diseases or even epidemics in flood-ravaged areas.
</P>
<P>
Floods have caused serious damage to a number of medical
facilities in Heilongjiang and Jilin provinces. More than 1,100
Heilongjiang medical institutions have sustained damage, with
losses of facilities, medical supplies and equipment surpassing 74
million yuan (nine million US dollars). More than 100 medical
institutions in Jilin have sustained losses totalling 10 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Ministry of Health note the most important
work at the moment centers on disinfecting and sanitizing
residential areas in order to prevent the spread of germs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
