<HEADLINE> Ukraine's Imported Goods Prices Soar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Stores selling imported goods
here hiked their prices by 15 to 20 percent over the past two
weeks as Ukraine's currency hryvnya continued to depreciate.
</P>
<P>
A store manager said if hryvnya keep falling, prices of
imported goods here might rise again.
</P>
<P>
A bottle of vegetable oil went up from 2.8 hryvnyas two weeks
ago to 3.8, up 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
Observers say the value of hryvnya was dropping rapidly because
of the Russian financial crisis and the falling ruble.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of hryvnya to the U.S. dollar set by the
National Bank on Monday reached the ceiling of foreign exchange
corridor of 2.23 to 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
