<HEADLINE> Kohl: G-7 Summit Little Help Given Russian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
said Tuesday that a proposed emergency summit meeting of the G-7
group of seven Western industrialized nations would offer little
help at the moment given the unsolved Russian government crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Bonn, Kohl said that he would support
such a summit provided that it could achieve concrete results.
</P>
<P>
"But now we even do not know who will be prime minister in
Moscow," Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Western leaders were staying in close
contact with each other following the development in Russia.
</P>
<P>
"The message to Moscow must be: Stay cool and do nothing to go
back to the past," Kohl said, adding that otherwise it would be
difficult for Western nations to offer moral support.
</P>
<P>
The proposal for an emergency G-7 summit meeting was made by
Japanese officials on Sunday but has not yet got any warm response
from other members.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi reportedly said Sunday that
he would favor a summit provided "we have a G-7 agreement on a
concrete package of measures." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
