<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Pledges to Continue Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin told his U.S. counterpart Bill Clinton on Tuesday that his
country will stick to the course of reforms.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no retreat from what the reforms have
achieved," Yeltsin was quoted as saying in the first round of
talks with Clinton in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Sergei Yastrzhembsky, Yeltsin's press secretary, told the
Russian Public Television Station that the two leaders extended
their planned meeting in a narrow format to "cover the agenda in
a more dynamic manner."
</P>
<P>
He said Yeltsin replied in detail all Clinton's questions, and
evoked a positive reaction from Clinton, who stressed "absolute
commitment to principles of democracy, market economy and
expressed confidence that Russia will find the way out of the
crisis."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also spoke of Washington's unconditional support to
Russia's course along that line and its readiness to consider
various forms of assistance, Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
As widely expected, Clinton did not speak about any specific
forms of financial and economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president is scheduled to have more meetings with
Yeltsin on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He will also meet with other major political players of Russia
Wednesday, including speakers of both houses of parliament, Moscow
mayor Yuri Luzhkov, Krasnoyarsk region governor Alexander Lebed,
Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov, Our Home is Russia leader
Alexander Shokhin and Grigory Yavlinsky of Yabolo, the Itar-Tass
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Clinton came at a difficult time for Russia, which is
confronting a full-blown financial crisis and without a fully
functional government.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma, or lower house of parliament, on Monday
overwhelmingly rejected Yeltsin's nominee for premiership, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, in the first round of voting.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has renominated Chernomyrdin again, but Duma speaker
Gennady Seleznyov said the nomination will most likely be
rejected again in the second round of voting scheduled for Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian constitution, if the Duma blocks the
premier's nomination three times, the president will have to
select a new nominee or dissolve the lower chamber.
</P>
<P>
A political agreement aimed at averting such a scenario,
signed by representatives of the president, the government and
both houses of parliament, was wrecked at the last minute when
major opposition parties balked.
</P>
<P>
Despite rejection of his nomination on Monday, Chernomyrdin is
expected to submit a roster of the new government to Yeltsin later
today. Bosses of key ministries, such as defense, foreign affairs,
interior, will retain their posts.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin was appointed acting prime minister August 24 when
Yeltsin abruptly fired the four-month-old cabinet of Sergei
Kiriyenko, after an effective devaluation of the ruble and a de
facto default on Russia's foreign debts that sent prices rocketing
and securities diving to record lows. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
