<HEADLINE> S. Korea Urges DPRK to Stop Missile Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korea Tuesday urged the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) to stop development
of ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
"We urge the North to stop missile development and participate
in international efforts to control missiles," said presidential
spokesman Park Jie-won in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Monday, the DPRK test-fired a newly developed medium-range
ballistic missile, which flew over Japan and fell into the Pacific
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The missile was confirmed to be a brand-new "Taepodong 1" with a
range of 2,000 kilometers, according to the South Korean Defense
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said Seoul will closely consult with the United
States and Japan to deal with the latest developments of the
DPRK's missiles issue.
</P>
<P>
"Seoul will strongly counter Pyongyang's 'Taepodong 1' firing
in concert with Washington and Tokyo," said Defense Minister Chun
Yong-taek before his departure Tuesday for a three-day visit to
Japan.
</P>
<P>
At an emergency meeting earlier Tuesday, the South Korean
government discussed countermeasures to North's missile
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
