<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Turkmenistan Sign Joint Statement (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
and visiting Turkmenistan President S. A. Niyazov signed a joint
statement of the two countries here on Monday, aiming to further
develop their bilateral friendship and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The statement says China and Turkmenistan share a common wish
to consolidate bilateral ties and strengthen the traditional
friendship between their peoples, and the two countries firmly
believe that the development of Sino-Turkmenistan friendship and
cooperation is in accordance with the basic interests of their
peoples, and benefits the peace, stability and security of Asia.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reiterated their adherence to the two joint
communiques signed after they established diplomatic relations on
Jan. 6, 1992, and the purposes and principles of the United
Nations Charter.
</P>
<P>
China and Turkmenistan expressed their determination to develop
a long-term and stable friendship and cooperation on the basis of
equality, fairness, mutual respect for sovereignty and territorial
integrity, and non-interference in each other's internal affairs,
and conformance with established principles of international laws.
</P>
<P>
"We have both the political willingness and a necessary
potential to further expand our overall cooperation," the two
countries agreed in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will continue contacts and dialogues at all
levels including exchange of visits between high-ranking officials
to discuss bilateral issues and affairs of common interest in the
region and worldwide, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed to enhance cooperation and regulate their
positions within the framework of the United Nations and other
international organizations, it stated.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will strengthen communication and cooperation in
the fields of science and technology, culture, education, health,
news media and tourism, it stated.
</P>
<P>
To guarantee the legal rights of citizens of one nation when
within the borders of the other, they also agreed to enhance
cooperation in the field of civil and criminal judicial aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Turkmenistan Sign Joint Statement (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two sides reiterated the great significance of developing
bilateral economic and commercial ties, and vowed to promote
cooperation in those fields.
</P>
<P>
They plan to improve the legal basis for economic and
commercial ties, and businesses of the two countries will be
encouraged to create direct contacts, and commit to trade,
economic and technological cooperation in various ways.
</P>
<P>
For the same purpose, Customs departments of the two countries
would also begin cooperation.
</P>
<P>
According to the joint statement, both agreed that cooperation
in the field of energy would be significant for their economies,
and would expand cooperation in energy exploitation, production
and transportation to international markets.
</P>
<P>
To enlarge their cooperation in cross-border transportation and
raise the economic efficiency of each country's commercial traffic
lines, they will create conditions for each other side to make use
of their airports, seaports, railways, highways and oil pipelines,
the statement also said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides, on the principle of equality and mutual benefit
and in consideration of their own real capacity, agreed to
cooperate in protecting and improving the environment, overcoming
the results of ecological damage and natural disasters,
sustainably using natural resources and preventing desertification.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will cooperate in the fight against any
organized cross-border criminals such as illegal traffic in
narcotics, psychological drugs, drug materials and illegal border
crossings.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to exchange information on laws, and to
cooperate in making and implementing laws.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that both sides were against national
splittism of any form, against stirring up conflict between
countries and nations, and that they would not allow any
organizations or forces within the border of one side to do
anything against the other side.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan reaffirmed that the People's Republic of China is
the sole legal government of China, and that Taiwan is an
inalienable part of Chinese territory, and made clear that it
would not establish any kind of official relations or commit any
kind of official contacts with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
China reiterated its support of Turkmenistan's efforts to
safeguard independence, sovereignty and territorial integrity,
consolidate its national economy, and maintain stability.
</P>
<P>
China respects the neutrality of Turkmenistan, the statement
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian-Israeli Security Agreement May be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians have said a
satisfactory second Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank means a
chance for an enhanced security cooperation with Israel, the
Haaretz newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted sources close to the Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations as making the remark following talks between the
U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) station chief in Tel Aviv
and top Palestinian security officials last week.
</P>
<P>
The talks, reported for the first time Tuesday, were held with
an aim to help the Israelis and the Palestinians reach an
agreement on a CIA-brokered memorandum of understanding (MOU) on
security cooperation, Haaretz said.
</P>
<P>
The MOU, which dealt with a wide variety of security issues,
was drawn up last December by representatives of the CIA and the
Israeli and Palestinian security establishments.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, Israel acknowledges that it also has
terrorists and agrees to deal with them in the same way as it
demands that the Palestinians deal with theirs.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu rejected it for
equating Israelis with the Palestinians as a potential source of
terror. Senior Israeli officials detailed in June its concerns
on incorporating new aspects to the MOU.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz quoted the unnamed sources as saying that the
Palestinians have rejected a draft agreement prepared by
Washington in early July because "it was dictated to them by the
U.S. without consultation."
</P>
<P>
But the sources said the Palestinians are now hopeful that
common ground would be found for an enhanced security cooperation
agreement if the issue of a 13 percent Israeli withdrawal from
the West Bank could be resolved.
</P>
<P>
One of the remaining issues regarding the redeployment is how
long the 3 percent of land to be designated as a Palestinian
nature reserve in the West Bank would exist under Israeli
restrictions, and when it would be transferred to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonoth, the largest circulated newspaper in Israel,
disclosed Monday for the first time that Israel has sent the
Palestinians an agreement defining the nature of the 3 percent
areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, Israel would maintain overriding
security responsibility in these areas which would be designated
as "Green Areas" or "Nature Reserves," and "there will be no
construction or inhabitation in these areas during the interim
period and until the permanent status agreement is reached."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
