<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier Urges Tree Planting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese premier Zhu Rongji
today called for accelerated efforts to plant more trees to
improve environment.
</P>
<P>
The premier said torrential rains combined with abnormal
weather conditions have caused heavy flooding in both the southern
and northern part of the nation. However, according to Zhu, the
disaster has, at least in part, been due to rampant deforestation
which led to serious erosion and in turn silting which raised
water levels and blocked the normal flow in river channels.
</P>
<P>
"The Party and central government have attached great
importance to forestation and both water and soil
conservation. Unfortunately, implementation of related policies
has been far from satisfactory," said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin recently quoted Engles as saying that
people should not be intoxicated with their triumphs over nature,
since nature takes revenge on human beings for each of their
success, which would in turn offest the success, according to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
He cited numerous worldwide examples of the destruction of
forests for the expansion of farmland eventually yielding nothing
but barren land.
</P>
<P>
The State Council announced a 1997 decision to ban logging in
the upper reaches of the Yangtze and Yellow rivers, with the ban
set for gradual implementation throughout northeast China.
</P>
<P>
China can supplement the reduced timber output by increasing
less expensive imports of timber products, said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
The premier made the remarks during his fact-finding tour of
flood-ravaged areas in northeast China. The remarks came during a
meeting with Ma Yongshun, a national model worker. Ma, a retired
model lumberjack, felled 36,000 trees prior to his retirement in
1982. He and his family have since won honors for planting 46,500
trees.
</P>
<P>
Zhu praised Ma for his contributions while urging people of the
entire nation to follow his example and plant more trees to ensure
the well-being of future generations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
