<HEADLINE> Members of HK Hospital Authority Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Hospital
Authority (HA) endorsed its working planning for 1999 to 2002
after discussions during its board meeting here Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of the HA's planning are to "sustain quality
improvement and monitor service delivery" and "ensure its
accountability to the stakeholders" with an output and
outcome-based resource allocation.
</P>
<P>
It will focus its planning on further strengthening its core
basic services using the tools developed in recent years, such as
clinical audit, risk management, quality improvement with process
indicators in the delivery of care and evidenced-based clinical
practice.
</P>
<P>
The HA will also maintain close liaison with the government
policy bureaus on health care reforms and systems so as to ensure
the formulation of the appropriate corporate strategies.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the members were updated on the progress of HA's
business support initiatives and discussed the way forward in
facilitating hospitals to implement changes in supporting services
to enhance quality of patient care.
</P>
<P>
Now, a total of 17 public hospitals have completed their
phasing-out program of ozone depleting substances. The current
schedule is for all HA hospitals to be free of identified sources
of ozone depleting substances by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Work has been undertaken in the past several years to improve
overall security management. Each hospital has now designated a
security officer or established a Security Steering Committee to
address security issues.
</P>
<P>
Currently the Non-Emergency Ambulance Transfer Service provides
 on average 1,600 patient-trips on a weekday. This workload
represents an increase of about 40 percent as compared to that of
1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
