<HEADLINE> Russia to Stick to Market Economy But With More State Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia will continue to build a
market economy, but could reimpose state control on the economy to
lessen its financial crisis, Russian President Boris Yeltsin said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Interfax news agency, quoting Kremlin sources, said Yeltsin
made the remark during his meeting with visiting U.S. President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who is in Moscow for a two-day summit with Yeltsin,
said the United States would continue to support Russia as long as
it continues its reforms.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin assured Clinton that his country will not step back
from reforms despite the grave economic situation, Interfax
reported.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin pledged Russia would continue to build a market economy
and a democratic society, but said tactical changes, including
tighter state control on the economy, may be necessary. 
</P>
