<HEADLINE> HK New Bus Operator Gears Into First-Day Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's new bus
franchise New World First Bus (NWFB) geared into smooth operation
Tuesday, the first day it started to run 90 routes on the Hong
Kong Island.
</P>
<P>
The first NWFB scheduled bus, Route 95, departed its depot on
time at around 5:00 a.m., marking the first day operation of the
new bus operator and putting an end to the 65-year services by the
old franchisee, China Motor Bus.
</P>
<P>
The changeover of bus franchise started late Monday night, and
was completed successfully at 4:00 a.m. Tuesday, according to the
Transport Department. NWFB took over depots, plants, machinery and
some 700 buses, and had them well-prepared for services.
</P>
<P>
Most passengers were satisfied with the NWFB services on the
first day despite a few complaints about poor air conditioning. A
Transport Department official said that traffic is usually heavier
on September 1, the opening day of schools, but the new bus
company handled well.
</P>
<P>
"We've made a very good start," said Adolf Hsu, managing
director of the NWFB at a news conference on Tuesday afternoon,
who pledged to offer safe, convenient and comfortable services for
passengers.
</P>
<P>
Hsu said that in the morning NWFB dispatched more than 580
buses on the road, and 650 drivers reported on duty. The company
operates 90 routes, with 88 routes taken over from the old
franchisee and two newly added.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 1,800 employees of China Motor Bus were
transferred to the new bus company, including 1,200 drivers, added
the managing director. 
</P>
</TEXT>
