<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A special buffer force is being
planned to get all the warring groups in Guinea Bissau to uphold
the cease-fire agreement signed on July 26, Nigerian Head of
State Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar said.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian leader made the remarks Monday in capital Abuja
when he received a special message from Guinea Bissau President
Joao Bernado Vieira, according to a New Nigerian report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar told Vieira's Special Envoy Avito Jose Da Silva,
Guinea Bissau Minister of Agriculture and Natural Resources, that
he was making efforts to get non-governmental organizations to
step up the provision of relief materials to thousands of
refugees in Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar expressed confidence in the Economic Community of
West African States (ECOWAS) to end the conflict in Guinea
Bissau.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS has suggested the establishment of a unity government
in Guinea Bissau as a way to solve the country's current
political crisis through parliamentary elections scheduled for
February next year.
</P>
<P>
An ECOWAS mediation delegation held separate meetings last
month with the Guinea Bissau government and the rebels led by
dismissed Chief of Defense Staff, General Ansumane Mane.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have been engaged in fierce fightings in several
parts of the country since early June before a cease-fire was
agreed on July 26. 
