<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK: Market Intervention is to Deter Manipulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region government said Tuesday that its recent
intervention into the stocks and futures markets is "to deter
manipulation in these markets by speculators who are attacking the
Hong Kong dollar at the same time."
</P>
<P>
"Our long-standing policy of non-intervention in the stocks and
futures markets remains unchanged," the government said in a
statement in response to the international rating agency Standard
and Poor's decision Monday to downgrade the credit ratings of Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Describing the S&AMP;P's decision as "unjustified," the statement
said: "It is not our objective to support the stock prices at any
particular level."
</P>
<P>
"As a responsible government we must take all necessary steps
to protect the stability and integrity of our currency and
financial markets when they are under speculative attack. Our aim
is to ensure a level playing field for market practitioners and to
ensure the efficiency of the markets," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The government's market intervention to fend off speculators
started on August 14, and, in the ten trading days till August 28,
boosted the Hang Seng Index by some 1,200 points or 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government said: "As the speculative attacks are still
ongoing, it is not possible for us to disclose the size of our
asset switch. Nevertheless, what we have acquired are all
good-quality assets which we will hold for the long term."
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the government noted, "S&AMP;P's estimates of
our deficit reaching three percent of our GDP, or about 40 billion
HK dollars (5.1 billion U.S. dollars), is way above our
estimates."
</P>
<P>
"In any case, our fiscal deficit this year is unlikely to have
a significant negative impact on the strong foreign currency
reserve position of Hong Kong. Our reserves stood at more than
eight times the Hong Kong dollar notes issued," said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The government also stressed that Hong Kong banks, highly
capitalized and well managed, are in a strong position to weather
the slowdown of the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Raises Price of Tap Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Beijing began raising the
price of tap water by an average of 32.6 percent today in a bid to
arouse public awareness of the importance of saving water.
</P>
<P>
The price of water for daily use for local residents has
increased from 0.7 yuan to one yuan (12 U.S. cents) per cubic
meter, and the price of water for industrial, commercial, and
administrative units has been raised from one yuan to 1.3 yuan per
cubic meter. And water used by hotels now costs 2.4 yuan per cubic
meter, 0.4 yuan more than yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has long had a policy of keeping water prices low, and
this has resulted in a serious water shortage and poor
water-saving awareness on the part of local residents.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Beijing Municipal Tap-water Company show
that Beijing residents used a total of 150.84 million cubic
meters water in 1992, and that by 1997 this figure hit 214.71
million cubic meters, up 42.34 percent in five years.
</P>
<P>
With the increased cost of water processing, the Beijing
Municipal Tap-Water Company, the only water supplier for the
Chinese capital, has been in the red since 1989. The municipal
government contributed subsidies of 187 million yuan to make up
the loss last year.
</P>
<P>
Beijing residents use only one-seventh of the average per
capita water use in China, and only one-twenty-fifth of the
world's per capita average use. Observers say the price increase
is the best way to ease the contradiction between water supply and
need in the city.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the increase in the price of water will not
have much effect on local residents. Concerned departments
estimate that it will cost only one more yuan per month for each
urban resident.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian-Israeli Security Agreement May be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians have said a
satisfactory second Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank means a
chance for an enhanced security cooperation with Israel, the
Haaretz newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted sources close to the Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations as making the remark following talks between the
U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) station chief in Tel Aviv
and top Palestinian security officials last week.
</P>
<P>
The talks, reported for the first time Tuesday, were held with
an aim to help the Israelis and the Palestinians reach an
agreement on a CIA-brokered memorandum of understanding (MOU) on
security cooperation, Haaretz said.
</P>
<P>
The MOU, which dealt with a wide variety of security issues,
was drawn up last December by representatives of the CIA and the
Israeli and Palestinian security establishments.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, Israel acknowledges that it also has
terrorists and agrees to deal with them in the same way as it
demands that the Palestinians deal with theirs.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu rejected it for
equating Israelis with the Palestinians as a potential source of
terror. Senior Israeli officials detailed in June its concerns
on incorporating new aspects to the MOU.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz quoted the unnamed sources as saying that the
Palestinians have rejected a draft agreement prepared by
Washington in early July because "it was dictated to them by the
U.S. without consultation."
</P>
<P>
But the sources said the Palestinians are now hopeful that
common ground would be found for an enhanced security cooperation
agreement if the issue of a 13 percent Israeli withdrawal from
the West Bank could be resolved.
</P>
<P>
One of the remaining issues regarding the redeployment is how
long the 3 percent of land to be designated as a Palestinian
nature reserve in the West Bank would exist under Israeli
restrictions, and when it would be transferred to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonoth, the largest circulated newspaper in Israel,
disclosed Monday for the first time that Israel has sent the
Palestinians an agreement defining the nature of the 3 percent
areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, Israel would maintain overriding
security responsibility in these areas which would be designated
as "Green Areas" or "Nature Reserves," and "there will be no
construction or inhabitation in these areas during the interim
period and until the permanent status agreement is reached."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
