<HEADLINE> Germany Gets Cash Boost for 2006 World Cup Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Germany cherished its cash boost
to bid for the 2006 World Cup as Chancellor Helmut Kohl pledged
on Tuesday to financially back for efforts to bring stadiums up
to modern standards in former East Germany.
</P>
<P>
Kohl said Berlin and Leipzig would get 100 million marks (57
million US dollars) each to help with renovation and rebuilding
projects for their stadiums.
</P>
<P>
"It was clear from the start that Berlin and Leipzig could not
apply to be World Cup venues without the help of the federal
government," the chancellor said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"I'm convinced the German Soccer Federation will present a
persuasive application to FIFA," Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic Stadium in Berlin and Leipzig's main stadium are
currently far from the standards of a modern venue and Berlin
authorities plan a complete overhaul of the Olympic stadium while
the Leipzig venue is likely to be totally rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
England, South Africa, Australia and Brazil have all announced
their intention to bid for the 2006 World Cup and FIFA will vote
for the venue in 2000. 
</P>
