<HEADLINE> Urumqi Airport Able to Handle Boeing-747s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Urumqi International
Airport in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region is
now able to handle large aircraft like the Boeing-747s as the
first-phase of its extension construction project came to an end
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The flying zone has been facilitated with the highest world
standards, with a runway of 3,600 meters able to support any type
of existing aircraft," said Bao Peide, deputy director of the
Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC), after on-the-spot
acceptance tests.
</P>
<P>
The second-phase of the project is also underway,
involving some 900 million yuan of investment, with 560 million yuan
going to a new terminal. The first-phase project, begun in 1994,
cost 104 million yuan, CAAC's Urumqi Administration director Zhang
Ruifu said.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang Airlines plans to invest more than four billion yuan
in the purchase of 10 Boeing aircraft over a three-year period,
Zhang said, adding that his company has bought three Boeing-757s
and five ATRs in the past two years.  
</P>
