<HEADLINE> Casagrande Banned Six Month for Doping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Italian cyclist Francesco
Casagrande was banned for six months after two positive doping
tests, the Italian Cycling Federation said in Milan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Casagrande, 28, was caught of unreasonable amount of
testosterone and epitestosterone in the Tour of the Trentino in
April and the Tour of Romandy in May.
</P>
<P>
The Italian who won the San Sebastian Classic and ranked fifth
in the world standings, claimed that the high levels returned was
due to natural causes.
</P>
<P>
"I took six or seven tests and they weren't always positive.
That means that my natural level of testosterone is variable," he
said.
</P>
<P>
To justify his innocence, Casagrande was willing to abide the
call of UCI, the sport's world governing body, to undergo
endocrinologic tests at the Biochemical Institute in Cologne
later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
