<HEADLINE> Iran Kicks off Military Maneuvers Near Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Islamic Revolutionary
Guards Corps (IRGC) began its maneuvers near Iranian-Afghan border
Tuesday morning to warn against the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
A total of 70,000 soldiers participated in the war game, which
is being held in Iran's northern Khorasan province, some 50
kilometers away from the Afghan border, the official IRNA news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The exercises, codenamed "Ashura-3," were held amid a spiraling
tension between Iran and the Taliban over the fate of missing
Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
The diplomats were allegedly kidnaped by the Afghan
fundamentalist group from Mazari Sharif in northern Afghanistan on
August 8 when the militia took control of the city.
</P>
<P>
Mullah Hassan Qalcheie, a close aide of the Taliban leader
Mullah Mohammad Omar, admitted Monday the captivity of Iranian
diplomats in a prison near Qandahar.
</P>
<P>
But Omar himself denied knowing the whereabouts of the Iranian
diplomats later in the day.
</P>
<P>
At the kick-off ceremony, the IRGC Commander Yahya Rahim Safavi
said that Iran is a peace-seeking state and does not seek
aggression against any country.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, Tehran will not tolerate mischievous acts
and disturbances on its borders by any country.
</P>
<P>
"I hope our friends have got the message and the enemies pay
heed to our advises," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim nation of Iran, armed with their Islamic might and
under the leadership of the supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei,
will repel any aggressions against the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
The IRGC commander also stated that Iran's policy in the
Middle East, Central Asia and Caucasus is to seek strengthened
Islam, peace and reconciliation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
