<HEADLINE> Adams Blasts Hoddle's World Cup Blunders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Former England captain Tony
Adams has slammed England coach Glenn Hoddle for World Cup
mistakes, four days before England's opening European
championship qualifier against Sweden.
</P>
<P>
In the opening extracts from his book "Addicted" which is
being serialised in The Sun newspaper, Adams accused Hoddle of
four big errors as England crashed out of France 98.
</P>
<P>
Adams said Hoddle was wrong to pick Alan Shearer as captain
ahead of him; he was wrong to humiliate David Beckham in front of
the players at training; he was wrong for treating the players as
kids in training and he was wrong to encourage Paul Gascoigne to
drink the night before dropping him from the final World Cup
squad.
</P>
<P>
It is an unprecedented attack by a senior England player on a
serving manager.
</P>
<P>
"I believe I should have been England skipper at the World
Cup," Adams said.
</P>
<P>
"Not only did I lead us during Euro 96 but after a decade as
England captain -- and three league championships -- I feel I
have proved myself and have the respect of my peers."
</P>
<P>
Adams said Hoddle had criticised Beckham while the team was
practising a free-kick routine, saying: "Obviously you are not
good enough to do that skill."
</P>
<P>
The Arsenal skipper said Hoddle's training sessions had been
too intense.
</P>
<P>
"I felt we were too regimented, treated like kids and expected
to do too much in training. It was too intense, a lot of the boys
were going berserk."
</P>
<P>
He also felt Hoddle was wrong to encourage the players,
including Gascoigne to drink the night before announcing his
final squad.
</P>
<P>
"Gazza was an ill man and Glenn did not properly understand
the illness of addiction," he said.
</P>
<P>
Adams balances his criticism by praising Hoddle as an
"excellent technical coach" who had revealed a "human caring
side" after the second round defeat to Argentina.
</P>
<P>
"He redeemed himself in many ways and showed himself a
promising international coach," he said.
</P>
<P>
Adams, a recovering alcoholic, also graphically describes his
own drinking, saying he would drink 20 pints of Guinness in a
session followed by two bottles of wine.
</P>
<P>
The book is being serialised in The Sun this week, the tabloid
newspaper which ran extracts from Hoddle's controversial World
Cup diary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
