<HEADLINE> Fifty-nine Teams Permitted by Nepal in Autumn Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 59 teams from 17
countries have been permitted to climb 26 peaks in Nepal during
the autumn season running from September 1 to November 15, the
Nepali Ministry of Tourism and Civil Aviation said in a press r
elease Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Among them, each team from Japan and Spain is allowed to
conquer the 8,848-meter Mt. Qomolangma, the world's highest peak,
the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Of the targeted peaks, six others are over 8,000 meters above
sea level, which are Manaslu (8,163 meters), Lhotse (8,516
meters), Dhaulagiri I (8,167 meters), Makalu I (8,463 meters),
Kanchenjunga (Main) (8,586 meters) and Annapurna I (8,091 meters).
</P>
<P>
The lowest peak to be conquered this time is Tengkoma (6,219
meters), the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Japan has as much as 15 teams to conquer 12 different peaks,
followed by Britain with seven teams for five peaks.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan mountaineering team of China, which plans to climb
all the 14 peaks over 8,000 meters above sea level in the world
and had scaled eight of them by May, aims this time at Lhotse,
the fourth highest mountain in the world.
</P>
<P>
Of the rest countries, Belgium, Colombia, Georgia, Greece and
Poland each has one team, Australia, the Czech Republic, Germany
and Italy each has two, France and Switzerland each has four,
while Austria, Spain and the United States each has five, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
During the spring season running from March 1 to May 31, Nepal
permitted 29 teams from 18 countries to climb 14 different peaks,
with seven teams allowed to climb Mt. Qomolangma. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
