<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Final Verdict In Taiwan Spy Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Municipal Higher
People's Court today made the decision to uphold the original
judgement on four Taiwanese charged with espionage.
</P>
<P>
On August 12, 1998, the Beijing Municipal No.1 Intermediate
People's Court made a ruling of first instance in the case of
four Taiwanese who were found to be working for the Taiwan
Military Intelligence Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Kou Jianming was sentenced to four years imprisonment and
deprived of political rights for two years. The other three --
Chen Shaoyu, Han Yueting and Zhou Changming -- were also
identified as having engaged in the crime of espionage, but were
exempted from criminal punishment.
</P>
<P>
Kou, Han and Zhou disagreed with the ruling and appealed to the
Municipal Higher People's Court, which then formed a collegiate
court to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
After reviewing the case, the collegiate court held that the
four Taiwanese were entrusted by the Taiwan intelligence
organization to collect political, economic and military
information in the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Their espionage activities all seriously endangered China's
state security and they should be punished in accordance with law,
said the collegiate court.
</P>
<P>
It also said the original judgement was correct and in
accordance with law and should be upheld. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Take Added Hit on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on Singapore
Stock Market Tuesday took a big hit as the newly-introduced
benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) lost 33.10 points to end at
823.33 points.
</P>
<P>
The index dived to an intra-day low of 811.82 points before
wobbling back slightly at close. Brokers said the market remained
weak and further fall was likely
</P>
<P>
The total turnover increased to 290.47 million units worth
345.68 million Singapore dollars (about 199.35 million U.S.
dollars). There were 271 losers against 39 gainers with 279
counters unchanged
</P>
<P>
ST Engg remained the most active stock of the day as it ended
on a turnover of 35.60 million stocks. It was followed by M Res
that had 16.40 million units done. IPC was next with 15.73 million
counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
F &AMP; N was the top gainer of the day as it gained 17 cents to
close at 3.00 Singapore dollars. YHS was up 12 cents to finish at
3.78 Singapore dollars. Hai Sunh inched up 5.5 cents to close at
0.255 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the down side, Asean was the biggest loser of the day as it
lost 1.34 U.S. dollars to end at 2.80 U.S. dollars. Creative 50
slid by 1.20 Singapore dollars to close at 16.10 Singapore
dollars. DBS shed 50 cents to finish at 3.82 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the sharp fall on the Singapore Stock Market was a
 reaction to Wall Street's 510-point overnight plunge.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market was also discouraged by Malaysia's
statement that the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) won't
recognize trades on CLOB International -- Singapore's
over-the-counter market for mainly Malaysian equities.
</P>
<P>
To discourage the trading of local stocks offshore, the KLSE
Monday announced that all dealings in Malaysian shares must be
done through the KLSE or by an exchange recognized by the KLSE.
But the CLOB which was set up in 1990 was excluded from its
recognition.
</P>
<P>
The KLSE also threatened punitive actions against those
Malaysian stockbroking firms which engage in indirect off-market
transactions and this rattled investors on market.
</P>
<P>
Selling further accelerated on Singapore market following a
speech by Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad in which he
said that central bank currency trading measures rendered the
Malaysia ringgit "meaningless" outside Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
