<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM: Ringgit to Be Pegged at Fixed Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's ringgit will
be pegged by Bank Negara (State Bank) to a fixed rate very soon,
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
With a fixed rate, people will know the real value of the
ringgit and "once we regain control of our exchange rate, we can
lower our interest rates and nobody else control our interest
rates," Mahathir said during a special interview on the country's
economic situation over radio and television which was telecast
live.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said a fixed ringgit might affect transaction costs
but with fixed rates, there was no need to hedge while the
transaction cost will not be subject to devaluation or revaluation
if paid at a later date, and also it would enable interest rates
to be lowered.
</P>
<P>
But the rate will be decided by market forces for the time
being, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that these are part of the "shocking" measures he
had mentioned before.
</P>
<P>
He said that the work of speculators was threatening to
impoverish the nation and that more measures would be announced
such as those amending laws related to stock market.
</P>
<P>
On foreign exchange control measures announced by Bank Negara
earlier Tuesday to curb speculation in the ringgit, Mahathir said
the capital controls would also enable the authorities to lower
interest rates, which in turn would make loans cheaper and
generate greater business activity.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit will no longer be a legal tender or have value
outside the country, Mahathir said, adding "However, as we know
that there is ringgit outside Malaysia, we will allow such ringgit
to be repatriated for a period of one month from today."
</P>
<P>
He said that Malaysia will continue to encourage genuine long
term investors while those already here would be able to continue
repatriating their profits.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investors wanting to set up production
facilities will be encouraged to come here as with a fixed
exchange rate they have a very good chance of making profits with
a minimal of costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
"On the other hand, stock market speculators who destroy
companies will be discouraged as asset stripping is not something
we want. Both locals and foreigners who buy shares will have to
hold them for one year," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the measures to control foreign exchange
announced by Bank Negara will continue until Malaysia is sure that
there are profound and fundamental changes in the international
financial systems.
</P>
<P>
The measures announced Tuesday were decisions made by the
government and not the central bank, he said, adding the measures
could be considered as a last resort and can be permanent.
</P>
<P>
"What we have done is to freeze ringgit in external accounts,
the ringgit is no longer legal tender overseas but is only legal
domestically," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday morning, Mahathir chaired a special Cabinet meeting
which, according to Malaysia's national news agency, discussed
measures to tackle the economic downturn faced by the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
