<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Ruling Party Wins Parliamentary Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's National
Election Committee (NEC) published on Tuesday the final official
results of July 26 Assembly election after the Constitutional
Council finished its hearing on poll complaints Monday.
</P>
<P>
The final official results and the allocation of seats was
announced Tuesday evening on TVK, the national television.
</P>
<P>
The NEC announced that ruling Cambodian People's Party (CPP)
has won the election with more than 2.03 million votes, while
Funcinpec of Prince Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) of Sam
Rainsy gained about 1.55 million and 700,000 votes respectively.
</P>
<P>
The result was just the same as the preliminary results
announced by NEC on August 4.
</P>
<P>
In the first Cambodian-organized election in decades, Second
Prime Minister Hun Sen's CPP cashed in with 64 seats, an absolute
majority in the 122-seat National Assembly, based on 41.4 percent
of the popular vote.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec netted 43 seats (31.7 percent) and the SRP 15 seats
(14.3 percent).
</P>
<P>
The remaining 36 parties got more than 12 percent of the vote,
but no seats under a seat allocaton formula verified by NEC.
</P>
<P>
About 4.9 million Cambodians voted out of the nearly 5.4
million registered, according to the NEC figures.
</P>
<P>
The NEC will provide copies of the official results to the CPP,
Funcinpec and the SRP. The results will also be sent to the
Constitutional Council and to King Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
The NEC said 48 hours will be given to permit political parties
to reconsider and change their list of candidates.
</P>
<P>
With a victory in the July 26 election, the ruling CPP has
secured enough seats in parliament to head the next government,
and incumbent co-premier Hun Sen, fielded by the CPP as the only
candidate for the premiership, will become Cambodia's next prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
But with the continuing rejection and protest against the
election result by Funcinpec Party and the SRP, the CPP is
unlikely to form a government alone because it has not gained two
thirds of 122 seats or 82 seats to form the government without a
coalition partner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
