<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Nearly 1 U.S. Cent Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
finished nearly one U.S. cent higher Tuesday as a
better-than-expected performance on the Australian Stock Exchange
pushed it to a sharply stronger close.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed in Sydney at 57.65 U.S. cents,
from 56.73 U.S. cents previously.
</P>
<P>
After an initial sell-off on the back of a huge Wall Street
fall, Australian shares recovered through the day to close less
than one percent lower.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished down 22.5 points at 2458.2,
more than 71 points above its early low of 2386.7 on a futures led
recovery.
</P>
<P>
"We are seeing a little bit of a recovery in all of the
markets," said Craig Busch, head of foreign exchange of St George
Bank.
</P>
<P>
On the day the Australian dollar ranged between 56.54 U.S.
cents and the late afternoon high of 57.69 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Busch said one reason behind the late afternoon volatility was
strong buying evident from U.S. funds.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said strength in the gold price had also offered
support to the Australian dollar. Gold closed in Sydney at 277.90
U.S. dollars an ounce, up from 275.55 U.S. dollars in New York
overnight Monday and higher from 275.05 U.S. dollars here locally
Monday.
</P>
<P>
the local currency was buying 80.20 Japanese yen from 80.35 yen
and 1.0103 German marks from 0.9998 marks. 
</P>
