<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets with Former Japanese PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Amidst drastic changes in the
post-Cold War world, China and Japan should make efforts to bring
a long-term, stable and friendly relationship into the next
century in light of the principles set forth in the Sino-Japanese
Joint Declaration and Sino-Japanese Peace and Friendship Treaty,
said Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen here today.
</P>
<P>
Qian made this remark while meeting with former Japanese Prime
Minister Toshiki Kaifu here today.
</P>
<P>
Qian praised Kaifu as a farsighted Japanese statesman and an
old friend of China. He welcomed Kaifu to again visit China on the
20th anniversary of the signing of the Sino-Japanese Peace and
Friendship Treaty. "The treaty is a reflection of the common
aspirations and determination of the people of both countries for
everlasting friendship in generations to come," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Qian also briefed the guests on the impact the lingering East
Asia crisis was having on China's economy, and the
counter-measures adopted by the Chinese government. "The operation
of the Chinese economy this year is generally good," he told the
guests.
</P>
<P>
Kaifu said he highly values the role played by China, an
influential country in world affairs. "No one should ignore it,"
he told Qian.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also had an exchange of views on the
international situation. 
