<HEADLINE> Australia Calls on Japan to Agree to Tuna Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Australia stepped up its
effort Tuesday for new talks with Japan in a bid to resolve the
long-running tuna dispute between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Australian Federal Resources Minister Warwick Parer said
Australia had told Japan in a diplomatic note that it believed
Japan's experimental fishing program breached the international
law.
</P>
<P>
The program, which ended Monday, involved Japan catching an
extra 1,400 tons of Southern Bluefin Tuna (SBT), a highly
migratory fish that spawns in the Indian Ocean, over its previous
6,065 ton quota.
</P>
<P>
Australia, Japan and New Zealand are the founding members of
the Commission for the Conservation of Southern Bluefin Tuna, an
organization that sets a total allowable catch and national
allocations for its member countries.
</P>
<P>
Japanese officials argue the program will help assess tuna
stocks.
</P>
<P>
But in a strongly worded statement, Parer said Japan only had
itself to blame if critics accused it of using the experiment as a
vehicle for a de facto quota increase.
</P>
<P>
Australia believed the program was inconsistent under customary
international law, the United Nations Convention on the Law of the
Sea and the Convention for the Conservation of Southern Bluefin
Tuna.
</P>
<P>
And Japan appeared intent on repeating the program next year
and possibly beyond.
</P>
<P>
"Our efforts to resolve the dispute are therefore directed at
ensuring this kind of program is not repeated and that appropriate
remedial action is taken with respect to the impact of this year's
fishing," Parer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"As a first step we are seeking Japan's agreement to
negotiations (under the SBT Convention), aimed at resolving the
dispute within 30 days - given the importance of this matter, we
urge Japan to join us at the negotiating table as a matter of
urgency."
</P>
<P>
The dispute between Japan and Australia has already seen
Australia ban Japanese tuna boats earlier this year from fishing
in Australia's Exclusive Economic Zone and Australian ports,
except in emergencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ACFTU President Meets Singaporean Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Wei Jianxing, president of
All-China Federation of Trade Unions (ACFTU), said today that
China values its friendly and cooperative ties with Singapore and
China is satisfied with the fruitful cooperation in various fields
between the two countries in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Wei, also member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Party,
made the remarks during a meeting here this afternoon with a
delegation led by Lim Boon Heng, general secretary of the National
Trade Union Congress of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Wei said it is imperative for China and Singapore to reinforce
their relations in every area, especially in economy and trade,
under the current international situation. China is ready to forge
a even closer relationship with Singapore oriented towards the
next century.
</P>
<P>
Wei briefed the Singaporean visitors on China's economic
situation and its ongoing flood fighting campaign.
</P>
<P>
He said that the heroic spirit demonstrated by the Chinese army
and citizens in controlling the flood shows the cohesion of the
Chinese nation when confronted with difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Wei also voiced his thanks for the donation from the
Singaporean visitors to the flooded areas.
</P>
<P>
He continued that the different ideology and social systems
between China and Singapore have never prevented the exchange and
cooperation between the trade unions of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The ACFTU hopes to further the ties with its singaporean
counterpart, Wei noted, adding that this would not only promote
the mutual understanding between the two peoples, but also serve
the healthy development of the collaboration between the trade
unions of the Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Lim expressed his solicitude to China's flood-hit regions and
said that although the donation from delegation is not much, it
shows the friendship of the Singaporean people towards their
Chinese counterparts.
</P>
<P>
He voiced the hope that the trade unions of the two countries
would strengthen their contacts and cooperation to contribute to
the mutual understanding of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
The host and guests also exchanged views on the financial
crisis in Asia and other issues.
</P>
<P>
The delegation arrived here Monday at the invitation of the
ACFTU. 
</P>
