<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares Tuesday
dived almost four percent in an early sell-off inspired by a
plunging Wall Street, but a spate of afternoon bargain hunting
hauled the market off its lows to close only 0.9 percent lower.
</P>
<P>
After initial panic, investors brushed aside the second biggest
points fall on Wall Street to seek cheap stocks in anticipation
that the United States market will bounce back Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index finished 22.5 points down at
2458.2.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was down 40.2 points at 4368.8, with
banking stocks leading the afternoon recovery.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank was up 2.7 cents at 21.65 Australian
dollars, more than 1.00 Australian dollar above its early low,
while Commonwealth Bank of Australia ended 7.5 cents higher at
18.73 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank lost 23.2 cents to 8.60 Australian dollars, off a low
of 8.28 Australian dollars, while Westpac bank was steady at 9.30
Australian dollars, recovering from 8.80 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index recovered to be 8.3 points lower at
907.8 while gold stocks performed against the trend.
</P>
<P>
Diversified miner BHP dropped 31 cents to 11.75 Australian
dollars on volume of more than 8 million shares, its first time
below 12.00 Australian dollars since December 1992.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto lost 36.8 cents to 16.592 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was up 3.5 points at 847.1 as the bullion price
improved 2.60 U.S. dollars per ounce to be trading around 277.60
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 303.43 million shares traded at a value
of 1.137 billion Australian dollars (655.48 million U.S. dollars),
with falls outnumbering rises by 730 to 414. 
</P>
