<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Merger, Low Prices Shake Kenyan Oil Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's oil sector is bracing
for major changes following moves by some of the key players to
improve efficiency, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
Among these key players are Caltex with its announcement of
major staff and structural changes and BP following its merger
abroad with American oil giant Amoco in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
The moves by the three large oil companies come in the wake of
two big events in the petroleum industry globally -- the economic
crisis in Asia and the subsequent decline in the demand for oil,
the local analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The low demand has depressed world oil prices now at their
lowest in a decade, according to Tuesday's Daily Nation
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Shell/BP Kenya Limited, which manages the
operations of the two brands, was forced to deny press reports
that BP would divest from Kenya following the merger with Amoco.
</P>
<P>
But the report highlighted concerns in the local market that
changes overseas may have negative impact on Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The BP-Amoco merger early last month meant a slash of 6,000
staff from the total 100,000 worldwide. Fears are high that this
may happen in Kenya where BP has invested.
</P>
<P>
Caltex announced in July that it would reduce staff and change
its trade patterns in order to survive with the bottom line being
cost-cutting. The move was said to be a response to increased
competition and the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The new changes to its global operations are to be effected by
September 15 and begin with staff changes in Kenya, including the
scrapping of the managing director's position previously held by
Robert Hakim, who was re-deployed overseas.
</P>
<P>
Caltex said in a statement that the position would not be
filled and would cease to exist in the company's new structure.
It is expected some other positions may also be phased out
gradually.
</P>
<P>
In July, oil prices fell to 12 Dollars a barrel, representing
a six-Dollar drop since 1997 and have now registered the lowest
in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Large amounts of oil held in stock and in transit are blocking
an immediate recovery in world oil prices, experts indicate.
</P>
<P>
They agree that the recovery of oil prices now is more
unlikely after the recent damage to the Russian economy prompted
by the devaluation of the Rouble.
</P>
<P>
The merger by BP and Amoco to create BP Amoco, with BP
controlling 60 percent, has been described as the largest
industrial merger ever, creating the third largest oil company in
the world.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, the merger is expected to strengthen BP's presence
now that it has greater financial muscle. Experts said this may
see it bolster its position as the Kenya market leader.
</P>
<P>
Other oil companies may be forced to go to the drawing board
to re-define their strategies.
</P>
<P>
Already the industry is involved in what has emerged as a
cut-throat competition, evidenced in the recent tender award by
Kenya Power and Lighting Cooperation (KPLC) to Mobil Oil to
supply the Westmont Power barge in Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
Shell, Kenol, Total and Caltex all complained in letters to
KPLC that the tender for the supply of 15,000 tons of light fuel
to the barge had been done without an open tender system.
</P>
<P>
They claimed the tender favored Mobil, a recent re-entrant
into the Kenyan market having pulled out 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the recent global changes in the oil sector and a
crowded competition in Kenya mean some of the new licensed oil
companies may have a hard time making inroads into the market.
</P>
<P>
The recent heavy advertizing by Engen of South Africa and the
launch of lubricants into the oil scene, including plans to begin
petrol station outlets by next year are just part of the plans by
new entrants.
</P>
<P>
The National Oil Corporation has opted to enter into the
retail business by putting up petrol stations in the key towns.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan oil market is currently dominated by BP-Shell with
nearly 27 percent, Caltex about 25 percent, Total 16 percent,
recent entrant Mobil at 15 percent while Kenol and Kobil share 14
percent according to estimates by industry experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
