<HEADLINE> Egypt, France to Start Extensive Diplomacy for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and France are to start in
a few days extensive diplomatic efforts to draw up the final
formula for their jointly-proposed international conference to
salvage the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Ambassador to France Ali Maher, in an interview with
Egypt's Middle East News Agency Tuesday, said a ten-member
committee comprising Egyptian and French experts will meet early
this month in Paris to draw up a joint working paper on the final
arrangement for the proposed conference.
</P>
<P>
The agenda, the participating countries, the date and venue of
the conference will be included in the paper.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and his French counterpart Hubert
Vedrine will look into the relevant details on the fringe of the
meetings of the United Nations Assembly meetings in New York this
month, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Maher disclosed that intensive contacts are being held with the
U.S. administration on this matter. Moussa, Vedrine and
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright contacted each other by
phone several days ago on how to make the conference successful.
</P>
<P>
The idea of the international peace conference was conceived
when Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak met with his French
counterpart Jacques Chirac in Paris in May.
</P>
<P>
Peace process between the Palestinians and Israelis has been
stalled for 17 months, while Israel's negotiations with Syria and
Lebanon have been derailed since 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
