<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Trade Deficit Decreases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The first half of 1998
witnessed a decrease in Cyprus' trade deficit by 1.2 percent
compared to that of the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released Tuesday by the Statistics and
Research Department, imports totaled 938.3 million Cyprus pounds
(1,876.6 million U.S. dollars) in the period January-June 1998
compared with 938.6 million pounds (1,877.2 million dollars) in
the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Total exports were 315.6 million pounds (631 million dollars)
compared to 308.5 million pounds (617 million dollars) in
January-June 1997.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the trade deficit totaled 622.7 million pounds
(about 1,245.4 million dollars), 7.4 million pounds (14.8 million
dollars) less than that in the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The report says the European Union (EU) countries' exports to
Cyprus accounted for 52.5 percent of Cyprus' total imports
compared with 47 percent during January-June 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the EU countries imported 58.1 percent of exported
goods from Cyprus followed by the Arab countries with a share of
22.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The corresponding shares for the EU and Arab countries in
Cyprus' exported goods in January-June 1997 were 55.3 percent and
25.7 percent respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
