<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Sharply Higher in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed sharply
higher in Tokyo Tuesday despite a dramatic fall on Wall Street
overnight.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed at 14,369.63, up 261.74
points, or 1.86 percent, from Monday after falling more than 400
points in the opening minutes of trading.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, rose 3.66 points or 0.33 percent to 1,110.15.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section came to an estimated 430 million
shares, almost unchanged from Monday's 433.97 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank led all shares in volume for the fourth straight
trading day.
</P>
<P>
Following Monday's sharp fall in New York stock market, where
the the Dow Jones Industrial Average slid 512.61 points, the
second largest fall in the Dow's history, Nikkei plunged 443.15
points to 13,664.74 in the opening minutes of trading.
</P>
<P>
But stocks rebounded later on signs that the New York market
may rise Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Traders noted that futures contracts on the S and P 500 index,
a major indicator of Wall Street stocks, were higher on the
Chicago-based Globex 24-hour trading exchange.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,341 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outnumbered gainers 597 to 572, with 150 issues ending unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
