<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Niger, Cameroun Resolved to Boost Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria, Niger and Cameroun
have decided to deploy more soldiers and policemen along their
borders to flush out armed robbers and rebels operating in border
areas.
</P>
<P>
A technical committee has been set up to work out an action
plan on how to eliminate armed robbers and rebels in Chad and
Niger, The Guardian newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Following a week-long meeting in Nigerian capital Abuja, said
the report, the three west African countries would mobilize their
soldiers, police and immigration officers as soon as possible to
ensure their border security.
</P>
<P>
Malam Sule Abdulahi, Niger's Minister of Internal Affairs and
Security, was quoted as saying that the fight against armed
robbers and rebels was not only to save people's lives and
property, but also improve trade and commerce among the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
The minister who attended the just ended meeting in Abuja
noted that the provision of security in the border areas would
also ensure the smooth movement of goods and services along the
three borders.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held in the wake of an increasing rate of
armed robberies and rebel activities against the government of
Niger, which has terrorized local people. 
</P>
