<HEADLINE> Jordan to Boost Labor Exporting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's first state-owned
service for labor exporting will begin operation later this year
to help lower the country's soaring unemployment and increase its
foreign currency earnings.
</P>
<P>
The Jordan Professional Placement Company (JPPC) will help
Jordanians find jobs in foreign countries, especially in the Gulf
states, the semi-official Jordan Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"One of our biggest assets is producing Jordanians with high
academic and professional standards. We will organize and market
Jordanians abroad so they can benefit themselves and their country
by sending remittance back home," said Samer Majali, who
represented the government in setting up the JPPC.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanians working abroad used to remit billions of
U.S. dollars back home during the 1980s, but the boom cooled down
after the 1991 Gulf War as most of the Jordanian workers were
expelled due to Jordan's support for Iraq, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf War was set off by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the paper quoted some economists as saying that such
a plan by the JPCC is a feasible way to help the government tackle
the soaring unemployment rate, whose official figure is 15 percent
and independent figure 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, with a population of 4.6 million, has about 300,000
citizens working abroad, receiving an average remittance of
2.1 billion dollars a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
