<HEADLINE> Iran Vows to Block U.S. Persian Radio Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran has vowed to do all it can
to block a U.S. Persian radio service yet to be launched, the
Tehran Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign Minister (Kamal Kharrazi) issued instruction to
Iranian diplomats to do all to block the plan that is against
international law and norm," Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmud
Mohammadi said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Tehran will closely follow the plan of the Radio
Free Iran and its possible broadcast material, and will try every
means to stop the anti-Iranian move.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. congress approved in April to allocate 2.5 million
U.S. dollars to launch the Radio Free Iran, which is scheduled to
start broadcasting in September.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that the U.S. move is a "candid interference in
Iran's internal affairs and is in no way acceptable."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also refuted a U.S. court rule on August 8, which
said that Iran must pay 65 million dollars in damages to three
former hostages held by pro-Iranian group in Lebanon in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
"How can one judge of a country issue a verdict against a
sovereign, foreign government?" he asked, adding that the ruling
was in fact a continuation of an anti-Iranian move "that is doomed
to failure."  
</P>
