<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eighth Yangtze Flood Peak to Sustain High Water Levels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The eighth Yangtze River flood
crest, which is passing central China's Hubei Province, is
expected to sustain high water levels on the middle and lower
reaches of the river for a long time.
</P>
<P>
The peak, which ranked fourth among the eight crests this
summer, passed Shashi at 2 p.m. Monday, raising the water level to
44.41 meters, or 0.81 meters below this summer's highest. The peak
was accompanied with a flow rate of 45,800 cubic meters per second.
</P>
<P>
The upriver Gezhouba Hydropower Project and some other
reservoirs helped reduce the flow rate by 2,700 cubic meters per
second to greatly relieve the intense pressure on waterlogged
levees in downstream areas, said Jin Xingping, deputy chief
engineer of the Yangtze River Water Conservation Committee.
</P>
<P>
However, the new crest will slow down the receding floodwaters
on the middle reaches, making it more difficult for downstream
areas to protect already flood-saturated embankments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Competition Picks up in Kenya's Milk Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Competition in Kenya's dairy
industry is picking up following the entry of new players to
challenge the Kenya Cooperative Creameries (KCC) in the
liberalized market.
</P>
<P>
Records at the Kenya Dairy Board (KDB) show that the
regulatory body has registered more than 60 private milk
processing companies since the liberalization of the milk
industry five years ago.
</P>
<P>
There are also more than 300 registered milk bars across this
east African country, handling an average of 5,000 liters on a
daily basis.
</P>
<P>
KCC monopolized Kenya's milk market before its liberalization.
</P>
<P>
By now the amount of milk delivered to KCC had dropped by
about 40 percent to 600,000 liters daily from a peak of one
million liters at times. Sometimes it has gone down to 200,000
liters, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The KDB records indicate that some 33 licensed milk processing
companies are currently handling about 550,200 liters of milk
daily, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The leading private milk processing and packaging firms are
Brookeside Dairy, Premier Dairy, Meru Cooperative Dairy and Spin
Knit.
</P>
<P>
Most of them process nearly all the milk products including
pasteur milk, fermented milk, condenselk, cream, yogurt,
mala, cheese and butter.
</P>
<P>
The report said farmers favor the private companies and
hawkers as alternatives to KCC since they pay promptly for milk
delivered.
</P>
<P>
The low price of raw milk offered by KCC is said to be one of
the main reasons that have forced most farmers that earlier
supplied KCC with milk to divert to private dealers.
</P>
<P>
Farmers receive 14 to 15 Shillings (0.23 to 0.25 U.S. Dollar)
for a liter of milk delivered to KCC while the consumer pays 30
Shillings for the same amount of processed milk. The private
firms are said to be offering up to 18 Shillings per liter.
</P>
<P>
In response, KCC Managing Director J. P. Nyaberi recently
announced that the company was planning to restructure its
operations in order to fit in a liberalized economy.
</P>
<P>
Nyaberi said the restructuring would focus on down-sizing and
cost-reduction and increase the company's efficiency and enable
it to consolidate what remains of the milk market.
</P>
<P>
One of the key strategies to be implemented by the company is
the merging of some factories to avoid duplication of efforts and
ensure effective utilization of available resources.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the company will close down seven of its 11
factories and 13 of its 26 depots, according to the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Petroleum, Chemicals Output Up in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- China reported 22.8 billion
yuan (about 2.7 billion U.S. dollars) worth of petroleum and
chemicals output in July, up 2.9 percent from the same month last
year, according to figures released by the State Petroleum and
Chemical Bureau today.
</P>
<P>
This growth rate is 1.9 percentage points lower than that for
June, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The combined output value of the petroleum and chemical
industry for the January-July period totaled 167.05 billion yuan,
up 3.2 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics also show that the output-to-sales ratio
for petroleum and chemical products stood at 98.1 percent in July,
up 0.3 percent from June, and up 1.8 percent from July, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Production of nine of the 16 major petroleum and chemical
products, including phosphorus, fertilizer, sulphuric acid, nitric
acid, soda ash, pesticides and wheel, increased in the
January-July period.
</P>
<P>
The bureau also said that China produced 2.25 million tons of
fertilizer in July, with total output for the first seven months
reaching 15.52 million tons.
</P>
<P>
China produced 38,000 tons of pesticide in July, and a total
of 249,000 tons since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
A bureau official said the petroleum and chemical industry in
central China's Hubei suffered 68.57 million yuan in direct
economic losses due to severe flooding, which has forced 28
enterprises to suspend production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
