<HEADLINE> Iranian Hostages Are Alive in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry
Spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi has stated that the Iranian hostages
taken by the Afghan Taliban militia are alive and Tehran will
make efforts to bring them back safe.
</P>
<P>
In an interview carried on local daily Tehran Times Tuesday,
Mohammadi rejected the report of some Pakistani newspapers that
the Iranian hostages are dead.
</P>
<P>
"Our people in Afghanistan are alive," he said, "we are
exploring all avenues for their safety and return to their homes."
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Mullah Hassan Qalcheie, a close aide of the
Taliban leader Mullah Mohammad Omar told the Iranian official
news agency IRNA that the 11 Iranian diplomats and an IRNA
reporter are "safely" held in a prison near Qandahar, the
Taliban's headquarters in southern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Qalcheie said that the Taliban administration will release the
Iranian hostages as a goodwill gesture to improve its relations
with Iran, which refuses to recognize the Taliban rule over
Afghanistan and supports the ousted government of President
Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Iran stated that the Taliban has kidnaped 11 Iranian
diplomats, an IRNA reporter and 35 truck drivers on August 8 when
the Afghan fundamentalist group seized Mazari Sharif, Rabbani's
main stronghold in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Tehran has asked the Taliban to free the Iranian nationals as
soon as possible, threatening that it reserves the right to
"resort to any means" to release the Iranians.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps announced to launch a
grand maneuver involving 70,000 troops on Iran's northeastern
border with Afghanistan this week.
</P>
<P>
In a response, the Taliban on Monday warned Iran to limit the
maneuver inside Iranian border and not to pose any threat to
Afghanistan's territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise, the flames of war will cover Iran and its rulers
will suffer from its grave consequences," a Taliban "Foreign
Ministry" statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
