<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin-Clinton Summit to Center on Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of Russia and
the United States met in the Kremlin Tuesday in a summit that is
expected to center on Russia's economic crisis and political
stand-off.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who arrived here earlier Tuesday, laid a wreath at
the Unknown Soldier's Tomb in central Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders, in their first full-scale summit since March
1997, will discuss primarily the economic situation in Russia,
Yeltsin's press secretary Sergei Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
He said Clinton is keen to listen to Yeltsin's judgment of the
financial crisis and of ways to tackle the financial and economic
problems.
</P>
<P>
Clinton came at a difficult time for Russia, which is
confronting a full-blown financial crisis while the country is
without a fully functional government.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma, or lower house of parliament, on Monday
overwhelmingly rejected Yeltsin's nominee for premier, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, in the first round of voting.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has renominated Chernomyrdin, but Duma speaker Gennady
Seleznyov said the nomination will most likely be rejected again
in the second round of voting scheduled for Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian constitution, if the Duma blocks the
premier's nomination three times, the president will have to
produce a new nominee or dissolve the lower chamber.
</P>
<P>
A political agreement aimed at averting such a scenario,
signed by representatives of the president, the interim
government and both houses of parliament, was wrecked at the last
minute when major opposition parties balked.
</P>
<P>
Despite rejection of his nomination on Monday, Chernomyrdin is
expected to submit a roster of the new government to Yeltsin later
in the day. Ministers of the key ministries, such as defense,
foreign affairs, interior, will retain their posts.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin was appointed interim prime minister on August 24
when Yeltsin abruptly fired the four-month-old cabinet of Sergei
Kiriyenko, after an effective devaluation of the ruble and a de
facto default on Russia's foreign debts that sent prices rocketing
and securities diving to record lows.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is not expected to pledge any new financial assistance
this time around, although he would reiterated Washington's
support for Russia's economic reforms and democracy, observers
say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
