<HEADLINE> NZ Wine Exports Nudge Target Set for Year 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Annual New Zealand wine
exports have almost reached their projected value for the year
2000 already.
</P>
<P>
Before the end of the year, wine exports would exceed 100
million N.Z. dollars (about 50 million U.S. dollars), two years in
advance of the projected date, the New Zealand Press Association
(NZPA) Tuesday quoted the New Zealand Wine Institute chairman Ross
Spence as saying.
</P>
<P>
A variety of factors has resulted in compound growth rates of
more than 19 percent value and 13 percent in volume, he said.
Influences included expansion of the vineyard area and number of
winemakers, and increased international demand for New Zealand
wines.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent annual report, the vineyard area in New
Zealand has increased to 8,716 hectares, a rise of more than 40
percent since 1993, with further growth expected in the near term.
</P>
<P>
The past year has seen a continued increase in the number of
winemakers, from 262 a year ago to current 293.
</P>
<P>
In the year, New Zealand has harvested a record vintage of
78,300 tons marked by high sugar levels and excellent fruit
balance, and the country also has seen a record total sales of
wine amounting to 53.8 million liters.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand has become a net exporter of wine for the first
time, with exports reaching 97.6 million N.Z. dollars (about 48.8
Million U.S. dollars) a year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It also spoke of international challenges including increased
competition from Australia, the United States and Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Confident of Meeting Economic Goal, FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- China is confident of
realizing the 8 percent GDP growth target despite the lingering
Asian financial crisis and flooding in summer, said Zhu Bangzao,
spokesman of the Foreign Ministry, at the routine press conference
here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the measures adopted by the Chinese government early
this year, such as expanding domestic demand, increasing
investment in infrastructures, exploring both domestic and
overseas markets, have paid off. "The measures have been proven
effective and efficient," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the efforts, China has kept its currency stable and
the GDP growth in the first half year reached 7 percent amid a
general economic slowdown in other Asian countries, he said,
adding that such a rate is "relatively high" worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Under the leadership of the Chinese government, millions of
Chinese servicemen and civilians successfully are still fighting
high floods in the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River
in central and east China and the Songhua and Nenjiang Rivers in
northeast China.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu, the floods have adverse effects to the
economic growth in the regions and added additional difficulties
for the whole country to realize the set economic goals.
</P>
<P>
However, "with the courage and determination, the diligent and
brave Chinese people have the confidence to overcome all the
difficulties," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Chinese government has adopted a more active
financial policy and put more money on infrastructure construction
so as to push up domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
"All efforts combined will surely minimize the adverse effects
of the natural hazards," he noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
