<HEADLINE> Strike Delays Opening of Israel's New School Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Because of the breakdown of
negotiations with the Treasury, Israeli teachers' unions moved on
with the strike on Tuesday and thus resulted in the delay of
opening of the new school year.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that officials of the Treasury and the
Education Ministry will make more efforts later Tuesday to
persuade the unions to end strike.
</P>
<P>
Treasury officials said that teachers are demanding an 8
percent salary increase, while they will agree only to a 5
percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Avraham Ben-Shabbat, chairman of the Teachers Union, said that
teachers want to open the schools, "but not at any price."
</P>
<P>
He told the Treasury that "pay us a fair and equitable salary,
don't pay us like kids working at summer camps."
</P>
<P>
But Treasury wage director Yossi Kucik said that "what we have
offered the teachers is fair and we can not give in to their
demands."
</P>
<P>
He added that teacher's real wages increased 27 percent
between 1993 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the Education Ministry, 1.2 million students had
been scheduled to start the new school year on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
