<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Students in Flooded Areas Greet New Term in Tent School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nanchang, September 1 (Xinhua) -- It comes as a pleasant
surprise to nine-year-old Zhou Zhenzhen, whose primary school has
been immersed in water, that she can attend school today as the
new term begins.
</P>
<P>
Leaning on a newly raised grey tent on the Sanjiao Dyke, Zhou
said she will have classes in the tent on September 1.
</P>
<P>
Zhou's Ganfang Primary School in Jiujiang City in east China's
Jiangxi Province has been greatly damaged by the floods, so she
and her schoolmates must greet the new term in this temporary tent
school.
</P>
<P>
There are three tent schools along the Sanjiao Dyke and more
than 170 of them in Jiujiang City.
</P>
<P>
Ganfang Primary School is one of the 5,700 middle and primary
schools in Jiangxi Province which have been ravaged by the floods.
</P>
<P>
Early this August, the provincial government began to repair
the damaged schools, and reports from the Jiangxi Education
Commission said 72.8 percent of these schools have been repaired
or rebuilt, and another 20 percent have set up temporary schools
in storehouses, tents and other safe locations.
</P>
<P>
Song Leiming, an official of the Jiangxi Provincial Education
Commission, said that students whose schools are unable to open on
time will be sent to attend other schools nearby. In remote
places, teachers will go the villages to teach.
</P>
<P>
According to the commission, students in the flooded areas will
enjoy a partial or total tuition-fee waiver.
</P>
<P>
In Yongxiu County, each student will enjoy a two-thirds tuition
waiver, and those with particular difficulties can apply for a
further waiver.
</P>
<P>
The latest report from the Jiangxi Provincial Education
Commission said that about 5,350 schools with 2.23 million students, 93
percent of the total number hit by the floods, open on September 1
when the new term begins. The local government is making efforts
to help another 190,000 students attend school before October 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
