<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Students in Areas Affected by Flooding Return to School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Most of the 8.5 million
primary and secondary school students living in areas affected by
flooding returned to school Monday when the new semester began, an
Education Ministry spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
Those living in 10 provinces and cities along the Yangtze River
and other major rivers were the most seriously affected by
flooding this summer.
</P>
<P>
The disaster has affected 44,853 primary and middle schools,
and resulted in the collapse of some 3 million square meters of
classrooms. In addition, the disaster has caused problems for
56,400 families of teachers, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Educational departments at various levels have raised fund
through different channels to repair classrooms, rent civilian
houses and set up temporary buildings for the students, he said.
</P>
<P>
Other methods have also been adopted, including organizing
students to study in other provinces and teaching courses at the
students' homes.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said that some schools could not open on
schedule because of damaged or destroyed classrooms. The ministry
has issued a notice calling on local educational departments to
take more steps to ensure that all the students can return to
school in the autumn, according to the spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
