<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 07:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Denies Being Behind GCC Anti-Iraq Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has denied an Iraqi
allegation that it was behind a statement issued by the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) which demands Iraq's unconditional
implementation of the Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq accused Kuwait Sunday of drafting the statement, saying
the statement "dose not reflect the opinion of other GCC members,"
the Kuwait News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A Kuwaiti Foreign Ministry official said "the decisions and
statement of the GCC ministerial meeting were issued after lengthy
consultations and discussions."
</P>
<P>
"Iraq always rejected statements and resolutions issued by
international and regional organizations that condemned its
aggression against Kuwait," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi accusation was "meant to cast doubt on the GCC
states' continuous support to Kuwait," the official said.
</P>
<P>
The GCC statement was issued last Friday to underline the need
of Iraq's implementation of relevant U.N. resolutions and
expressing concern over its suspension of cooperation with the
U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Iraq suspended cooperation on August 5 with U.N. Special
Committee (UNSCOM) and the International Atomic Energy Agency,
which have taken charge of weapons inspections in Iraq since 1991
Gulf War, set off by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iraq accused the UNSCOM of being pro-U.S. in attempt to prolong
the U.N. sanctions, which were imposed on Iraq after the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance set up in
1981, groups Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the
United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
