<HEADLINE> Eastern China Continues to Lead Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua)-- Eastern China's 12 provinces
continued to lead China's economic development during the first
half of this year, according to the State Economic and Trade
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics from the commission show that the industrial
output of these provinces reached 1.953 trillion yuan, up 10.3
percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Their growth rate was 2.2 percent higher than that in central
China, and 4.5 percentage points higher than in the western part
of the country.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that five of the nine provinces with
industrial growth rates higher than the country's average are
located in eastern China.
</P>
<P>
The investment in fixed assets in the east reached
360.38 billion yuan in the first half, up 13.6 percent on a
year-to-year basis.
</P>
<P>
In the January-June period, retail sales in the east
amounted to 833.41 billion yuan, accounting for 59.6 percent of
the country's total. The annual growth rate in this sector was
8.2 percent, up 1.4 percentage points over the country's average.
</P>
<P>
Eastern China, which includes Beijing, Tianjin and Shanghai
municipalities, Hebei, Liaoning, Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Fujian,
Shandong, Guangdong and Hainan provinces, and Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, has long been the country's leader in economic
development, the commission said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
