<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 08:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Launch Program to Help Elderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon is working out a
nationwide program to provide the country's elderly people with
cheaper social, health and entertainment services, the Daily Star
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Ministry of Social Affairs were quoted as
saying that the program, being prepared by the ministry, will be
formally launched in 1999, the world's year for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
People aged 65 years and older will have free medical service
under the program, said Neamat Kenaan, the director-general of the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
They will also be given discounts on access to sports clubs,
cinemas, nightclubs and free or discounted transportation.
</P>
<P>
Kennan said the program will be launched with an awareness
campaign aimed at high school and university students.
</P>
<P>
"Posters and flyers, as well as TV and radio adverts, are
especially oriented to youth, warning them that they will one day
grow old and be depressed if society doesn't take care of them,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry recent statistics, some 6.9 percent
of the country's 3 million population are over 65 years old, which
means that Lebanon is a young society.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the percentage to increase when such a program is
implemented, as all elderly people will receive medical and social
services and live longer," the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
