<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Former Japanese Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese people are
confident and capable of winning the battle against the ongoing
heavy flooding and of achieving the goal set for this year's
national economy, President Jiang Zemin today told former Japanese
Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu.
</P>
<P>
"China will adhere to the policy of not devaluing its currency
of Renminbi in an effort to stabilize the overall regional
economy," Jiang said. "At the same time, we hope that Japan makes
its due contributions to ease the regional economic difficulties."
</P>
<P>
He said China-Japan relations are entering an important period
of inheriting the past and forging into the future at the turn of
the century.
</P>
<P>
"So long as we draw from past experience, China-Japan relations
can be given impetus in the forthcoming century," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
This year is the 20th anniversary of the signing of the
China-Japan peace and friendship treaty.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the treaty, with great significance, has
further consolidated the political basis for relations between the
two neighboring nations and reflected the common aspirations of
the two peoples to live in friendship from generation to
generation.
</P>
<P>
Kaifu expressed his sympathy and solicitude for the people in
China's flood-ravaged regions, saying that the Japanese people
fully understand the reason Jiang postponed his scheduled
September tour of Japan.
</P>
<P>
However, he continued, they expect this historical visit to be
possible at an early date.
</P>
<P>
Kaifu agreed with Jiang's viewpoints on Japan-China ties,
saying that Japan should properly deal with that period of history
and not follow the track of the overturned cart.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese side, he said, should keep to principles set in
the peace and friendship treaty and in the China-Japan joint
statement in a bid to further promote bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Kaifu and his party are here at the invitation of the Chinese
People's Institute of Foreign Affairs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
