<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Aviation Industry: Major Partner of Boeing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is in 1972 that China placed its first order for 10 Boeing
707 airplanes and the country has since become one of the
company's main customers by purchasing 289 aircraft in seven
Boeing series so far, accounting for 72 percent of its imported
airplanes.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, China and McDonnell Douglas, which was taken over by
Boeing last year, started a series of cooperative projects in
China, including assembling 35 MD-80s at the Shanghai Aviation
Industry Corp.; making 20 MD-90 trunk aircraft; and manufacturing
parts such as vertical fins, stabilizers, noses and tail
assemblies by manufacturers in the cities of Shanghai, Chengdu,
Shenyang and Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
"That was the turning point," Bracy said. "It marked the
beginning of our overall cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Since then, the two partners have joined efforts in setting up
several training centers both in Chinese cities and the U.S. city
of Seattle, where Boeing has its headquarters. They have also set
up a joint air traffic service group and a huge field service
network in China, with more than 40 Boeing engineers based in more
than 20 Chinese cities to solve technical problems.
</P>
<P>
Chinese engineers also have participated in the design of tail
assemblies for Boeing 737-700s, which began delivery last October.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, all the MD-80s assembled in Shanghai have been put
into use and the parts made in China have been installed in about
3,000 Boeing aircraft. The first Chinese-made MD-90 is scheduled
to come off the assembly line in November.
</P>
<P>
"Of our thousands of foreign partners, Chinese enterprises have
proved competitive for their high quality, low cost and prompt
delivery," Bracy said, adding that China has great market
potential, another reason for their successful cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Boeing is the world's leading airplane producer and has
produced more than 70 percent of the 11,500 passenger planes
flying around the world.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Civil Aviation Administration of China
(CAAC) confirmed Boeing's contribution to the development of the
Chinese aircraft sector.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to further cooperate with Boeing, especially in
developing and manufacturing new aircraft," said Wang Zhi,
director of planning for the CAAC.
</P>
<P>
"We chose Bracy to lead Boeing China in March of this year,
hoping that he would bring the cooperation to a higher and broader
stage," said Ron Woodard, president of Boeing's Commercial
Airplane Group.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
