<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Imposes Forex Controls to Curb Speculation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Tuesday
announced foreign exchange controls with immediate effect to curb
speculation in its currency ringgit.
</P>
<P>
The controls include the need for foreigners to get Bank Negara
(State Bank)'s permission to convert ringgit into foreign
currencies, the central bank's acting governor Zeti Akhtar Aziz
said at a press conference here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Approvals are required for the transfer of funds between
external accounts, she said, adding the steps to curb speculation
and minimize the impact of short-term capital inflows on the
domestic economy were vital in view of the significant fall in the
ringgit due to speculative attacks against it since July last
year.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the transfer to resident accounts is permitted only
until September 30, 1998, whereby approval is required thereafter,
and the withdrawal of ringgit from external accounts requires
approval except for the purchase of ringgit assets, she said.
</P>
<P>
For authorized depository institutions, all purchases and sales
of ringgit financial assets can only be transacted through
authorized depository institutions and for trade settlements, all
settlements of exports and imports must be made in foreign
currencies, she said.
</P>
<P>
On currencies held by travelers, effective October 1, 1998,
they (travelers) are allowed to import or export not more than
1,000 ringgit (about 250 U.S. dollars) per person, she said.
</P>
<P>
"There are no limits on the imports of foreign currencies by
resident and non-resident travelers," she said, adding the export
of foreign currencies by resident travelers is permitted up to a
maximum of 10,000 ringgit (about 2,500 U.S. dollars) equivalent.
</P>
<P>
She said the export of foreign currencies by non-resident
travelers is permitted up to the amount of foreign exchange
brought into Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Zeti said the ringgit would no longer be legal tender overseas
from October 1, 1998 and that those holding ringgit overseas will
not be able to convert the ringgit to any foreign currency
overseas unless they use the ringgit to buy Malaysian assets.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit can no longer be exchanged for other currencies
unless they are brought back to Malaysia, she added.
</P>
<P>
She said that there would be no restrictions for foreign
currencies as international currencies would still be traded in
Kuala Lumpur. "We would like to see the forex market develop in
Kuala Lumpur," she added.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia would return to the previous arrangement of free
capital flows once there is a discernible normalization of the
currency and financial markets, she said.
</P>
<P>
The acting governor said the measures would not impede foreign
direct investment flows as the foreign direct investors could
freely repatriate their profits and dividends.
</P>
<P>
To a question on whether the Malaysian central bank would like
to see other countries take similar measures to control foreign
exchange, she said a concerted effort to deal with the problem is
required before a greater problem unfolds.
</P>
<P>
However, it is up to other countries to decide on what measures
they should take, she said, adding that for Malaysia, it wants to
insulate its economy from the risks and vulnerabilities of adverse
external developments.
</P>
<P>
Zeti was of the view that the new measures would bring
stability to the ringgit "to a large extent" because trading of
the ringgit will be brought onshore.
</P>
<P>
"But Bank Negara would let the ringgit's level to be determined
by market forces," she added.
</P>
<P>
She said offshore ringgit will have to be brought back in one
month's time after which they would not be permitted except for
the import of no more than 1,000 ringgit (about 250 U.S. dollars)
per person.
</P>
<P>
She said this also applies to ringgit depositors in overseas
banks. In other words, this would cause the ringgit to be no
longer traded in other financial centers except in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
However, she said that this does not mean the foreign exchange
market will cease in Malaysia as exporters would still be required
to convert foreign currencies for exports and importers would
also have to convert ringgit into foreign currencies to pay for
their imports.
</P>
<P>
She explained that trade would not be affected in any way with
the implementation of the new measures as trade payments would be
made in major foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
She said what the central bank is doing is to target access to
ringgit funds by speculators.
</P>
<P>
Bank Negara wants to have a more independent economic and
financial policy according to domestic considerations, she said.
</P>
<P>
She added that the government would revert to free flow of
capital if the currency and financial markets go back to normal,
but this return must be sustainable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
