<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Radioactive Seeds Help Prostate Cancer Treatment, Says Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A study released Monday said
that implanting radioactive seeds in the prostate to treat early
stages of cancer may be as effective as surgery, and more
effective than external beam radiation.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted at Northwest Hospital in Seattle and
published in the latest edition of the journal Cancer, looked at
152 men during 10 years after they were treated with radioactive
seeds and, in some cases, beams of radiation from outside the body.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-four percent of them remained free of disease and had low
levels of prostate-specific antigen, or PSA, which can be an early
signal of the cancer, the study reported, adding that only three
patients died of prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
"It shows that brachytherapy is a proven, viable option for
treating clinically localized prostate cancer," said Dr. Haakon
Ragde, author of the study.
</P>
<P>
"This is just as effective as the best surgical results and is
more effective than conventional radiation beam results," he added.
</P>
<P>
The study is the first to observe brachytherapy patients for a
full 10 years, claimed Ragde, a urologist at the Seattle
hospital's Northwest Prostate Institute.
</P>
<P>
"Many men are now going to be opting for seed implantation
because of the numerous advantages it has in terms of reduced
morbidity, impotence and incontinence," said Dr. Subir Nag,
president of the American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
The American Cancer Society estimates 184,000 American men may
get prostate cancer this year and 39,200 may die of it.
</P>
<P>
Prostate cancer is the second leading cancer killer among
U.S. men after lung cancer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
