<HEADLINE> Over 1.5 Billion NZ Dollars Wiped Off Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of more than 1.5
billion New Zealand dollars (750 million U.S. dollars) were wiped
off the value of New Zealand shares before noon Tuesday as the
share market reacted to sharp falls on world share markets.
</P>
<P>
According to the Evening Post, a Wellington-based newspaper,
New Zealand's NZSE40 index, which measures the country's top 40
shares, slumped five percent shortly before noon.
</P>
<P>
In New Zealand, there were 86 falls in early trading and three
rises. Most of the blue chip stocks slumped. NZ insurance giant
AMP lost 1.5 NZ dollars to 23.10, troubled Brierley Investments
shed five cents to 64 cents, and Telecom fell 31 cents to 7.49 NZ
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Don Turkington of sharebroker Cavill White
Securities as saying the situation was "very very serious".
</P>
<P>
In the current environment, it is hardly surprising that
concerns about global recession have emerged, the paper quoted
local analysts as saying. 
</P>
