<HEADLINE> Chinese Aviation Industry: Major Partner of Boeing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Bill Boeing, founder of the
Boeing Company of the United States, hired a Chinese, Tsu
Wong, as its first designer 82 years ago. But he probably never
expected that China's aviation industry, which then did not exist,
might one day become a major business partner of this
international giant.
</P>
<P>
The latest Boeing Co. statistics show that China has bought
one-tenth of the firm's aircraft in the past three years; that
China and Boeing have jointly established one of the world's
largest airplane spare parts center in Beijing; that
more than one-third of the 8,500 Boeing aircraft flying around the
world are equipped with parts made in China; and that more and
more parts and aircraft are being manufactured or assembled in
China.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation with the Chinese aviation sector is the largest
and the most efficient part of Boeing's foreign business," said
Raymond Bracy, president of Boeing China Inc. "We've never done so
in any other foreign country."
</P>
<P>
According to the 41-year-old Bracy, the youngest of Boeing's
managerial class, former U.S. President Nixon's 1972 visit to
China in a Boeing 707, the Air Force One, resulted in not only the
normalization of diplomatic relations between the two countries,
but also the establishment of long-term business ties between
Boeing and China's aviation industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
