<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Incomes Lag Behind Men's in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Women's incomes continue to
lag behind men's, according to the latest household economic
survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows average income per person aged 15 years or
over was 472 New Zealand dollars per week, with 617 NZ dollars
for males and 380 NZ dollars for females (One NZ dollar equals to
0.4953 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The survey for the year to March 1998 was circulated here
Tuesday by Government Statistician Len Cook.
</P>
<P>
Households earned an average 49,225 NZ dollars before tax in
the year, or 944 NZ dollars per week, the survey shows.
</P>
<P>
Average household expenditure was 683 NZ dollars per week, up
three percent from the figure for the previous year.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, housing continued to be the most
significant item of household expenditure. In terms of every
dollar of household spending, 19 cents was on housing;
transportation accounted for 18 cents; 17 cents went on health,
education, insurance and other services; 17 cents were spent on
food; 14 cents went on running and equipping the home; 12 cents
were for books, newspapers, tobacco and alcohol; and only four
cents were spent on clothing and footwear.
</P>
<P>
Income from wages and salaries continued to be the single
biggest component of personal and household income.
</P>
<P>
The survey says that 33 percent of households had a home
computer in the year, up from 28 percent in the previous year; and
microwave ovens were present in 80 percent of households. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
