<HEADLINE> 65M Dollars Foreign Aid Committed for Bangladesh's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations' bodies,
international organizations and a number of countries have so far
committed or pledged relief assistance for Bangladeshi flood
victims in cash and goods valued at about 65 million U.S. dollars,
press reports said Tuesday quoting informed sources.
</P>
<P>
The United States, which has committed 200,000 tons of wheat
worth 40 million U.S. dollars, is likely to raise the amount to
260,000 tons, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Monday announced that it was providing
initial assistance of 1.16 million dollars for the flood victims,
according to a press release of the United Nations Development
Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
The release stated that the contribution included 260,000
dollars from the UNDP and OCHA (UN Office for the Coordination of
Humanitarian Affairs), 200,000 dollars from the World Food
Program, 500,000 dollars from UNICEF (UN Children's Fund) and
200,000 dollars from WHO (World Health Organization).
</P>
<P>
The funds provided by the U.N. agencies will be used for
emergency shelters, water purification tablets, high energy
biscuits, tube-wells and sanitation materials.
</P>
<P>
Other major donors include Kuwait which has announced a
contribution of two million dollars, and Australia which is
urgently going to ship 86,000 tons of wheat worth 17.2 million
dollars, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Donors also include Canada, the European Union, Germany, Japan,
 the Netherlands, Sweden, Switzerland and Britain. Some of the
assistance committed by the above-mentioned countries will be
channeled through non-government organizations and Red Crescent or
Red Cross, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
