<HEADLINE> S. Korea Shocked at DPRK Missile Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Presidential
spokesman Park Jie-Won said Tuesday that Seoul was shocked at the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea's test-firing of a missile.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking the day after the DPRK reportedly fired a
ballistic missile that overflew northeastern Japan and fell into
international waters in the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Park called on Pyongyang to halt its development of missiles
and join international efforts to prevent their proliferation.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Defense Ministry issued a statement to express
its grave concern about the test.
</P>
<P>
Unification Minister Kang In-Duk held a meeting on Tuesday with
ministers in related ministries to discuss policies toward the
DPRK following the missile test.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK has not confirmed the test firing. 
</P>
