<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras, Hingis Sail into Second Round at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Tope seeds Pete Sampras of the
United States and Martina Hingis of Switzerland sailed into the
second round as expected in the men's and women's competition at
the U.S. Open tennis championships here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who opened his bid for a record-tying 12th Grand Slam
title, beat Marc-Kevin Goellner of Germany 6-3, 6-2, 6-2, while
Hingis, who started to defend her title here, rolled over
Aleksandra Olsza of Poland 6-2, 6-0 in commanding style.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who has won five Wimbledon and two Australian Open
titles, is seeking his fifth U.S. Open championship to tie former
Australian star Roy Emerson's record for career Grand Slam
titles.Sampras is also looking to tie Fellow American Jimmy
Connors'modern-day record of five U.S. Open championships.
</P>
<P>
The 27-yearold dominated Goellner, serving 11 aces and
cracking 38 winners against only 17 unforced errors, winning in
only 84 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"It was a good start," said Sampras, "In the early rounds, you
like to get a feel for the court, get used to the surroundings. I
didn't get a chance to get comfortable last year."
</P>
<P>
Sampras was upset in the fourth round last year by Petr Korda
of the Czech Republic in the new Arthur Ashe Stadium at the
National Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
Goellner had nine aces but committed eight double faults. The
German had 27 winners but made 25 unforced errors and was unable
to hold off Sampras' attacking game. Sampras was successful on
five of eight break-point opportunities while Goellner could not
even force a break point during the three sets.
</P>
<P>
Sampras' seocnd round opponent will be young American Paul
Goldstein, who advanced to the second round when his opponent
Andrew Ilie of Australia, retired in the fourth set with an
undisclosed injury.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Hingis has not won a tour event since the
Italian Open in May and could lose the No. 1 ranking she has held
for the last 17 months to either Lindsay Davenport or Jana
Novotna at the conclusion of the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Hingis became the second youngest U.S. Open women's
champion. She won 12 titles, lost only five matches and came
within one victory of capturing the Grand Slam in 1997, but has
been unable to repeat that success this year.
</P>
<P>
Hingis has a tough second-round match against unseeded Iva
Majoli of Croatia, who beat her in last year's French Open
final.Majoli dispatched Germany's Anke Huber 6-3, 6-3 today.
</P>
<P>
No. 15 Alberto Berasategui of Spain became the first seed
player to fall in the tournament when he was ousted by former
top-ranked player Thomas Muster of Austria 7-6 (7-1), 6-2, 6-3.
Muster, who has been plauged by injuries, is unseeded this time.
</P>
<P>
In other matches involoving seeded men, ninth seed Karol
Kucera of Slovakia beat American Steve Campbell 6-4, 6-2, 6-4
while number 14 Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia, a first round loser
three of the last four years, cruised past Mark Woodforde of
Australia 6-3, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Eighth seed Andre Agassi of the United States breezed past
Sebastian Grosjean of France 6-4, 6-1, 6-4. Agassi is 45-8 on
hardcourts this year to lead all players in victories on the
surface and has won four titiles. He beat Sampras two times in
three meetings.
</P>
<P>
Among the seeded women, ninth seed Irina Spirlea of Romania,
who lost to Venus Williams of the United States in a memorable
semi-final match last year, downed Elena Likhovtsev of Russia 7-6
(7-0), 6-4; No. 11 Patty Schnyder of Switzerland fought off Yuka
Yoshida of Japan 7-6 (7-5), 7-5; No. 14 Dominique Van Roost of
Belgium stormed past Frenchwoman Julie Halard-Decugis 6-2, 6-2;
and No. 16 Ai Sugiyama of Japan eliminated Ruxandra Dragomir of
Romania 6-1, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Two-time champion Monica Seles of the United States, the sixth
seed, survived a first-set tiebreak to defeat Florencia Labat
7-6(7-0), 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Men's defending champion Patrick Rafter of Australia plays his
first-round match against Morocco's Hicham Arazi later this
week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
