<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hawaii May Pay Families of Organ Donors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Hawaii state government
is considering paying the families of organ donors in a bid to
improve its record for having the lowest number of donations among
the 50 U.S. states, Associated Press reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This has been discussed in the past and people all thought it
was a macabre idea, but let's be practical about things, let's
think about things because we can help people," Hawaii Governor
Ben Cayetano said at an unveiling ceremony last week of a
commemorative stamp for the National Kidney Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Hawaii faces the worst shortage of organs available for
transplants in the United States. Only seven organs have been
donated so far this year and a total of 18 donations last year
with a waiting list of 191.
</P>
<P>
Local officials cited several factors intensifying the shortage.
</P>
<P>
Among them, Hawaii is too far away from the mainland to import
organs, they said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, cultural and ethnic beliefs, particularly among
Filipinos, discourage donations because they are mostly Roman
Catholics who believe they need to be full in body and spirit when
they die.
</P>
<P>
U.S. federal law prohibits the sale of donated organs to
prevent creation of a potentially dangerous black market for
organs.
</P>
<P>
The officials said they believe certain payment to the families
of organ donors is needed in the island state. They also stress
the importance of educating islanders to overcome worries about
organ donation.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, 20,000 Americans received organ transplants last
year, but 4,000 died waiting for a donor. More than 55,000 people
are on the transplant waiting list, up from 16,000 in 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal to Launch New Immunization Program Against Polio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Nepal will launch an
immunization program against polio for the third year in a row on
December 7 this year and January 18 next year, The Kathmandu Post
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister K.B. Gurung was quoted as saying that more than
3.3 million children across the country will be immunized with
polio drops on the two days.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted a World Health Organization (WHO) report as
saying that every year 100 to 150 children aged under five in
Nepal suffer from polio, a disease which cripples children.
</P>
<P>
But a statement issued by the Nepalese side put the number of
children suffering from polio at nine in 1996 and 11 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"No polio patients have been recorded till date in the current
year, but we are working hard in searching out polio patients all
over the country," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The WHO report listed nations like Myanmar, Bangladesh, India
and Nepal as polio epidemic-prone zones.
</P>
<P>
At their ninth summit in May 1997, leaders of the member
countries of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation
(SAARC) -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka -- decided to designate December 7, 1997
and January 18, 1998 as "SAARC Polio Immunization Days."
</P>
<P>
The SAARC countries had decided to achieve the goal of
universal eradication of polio by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
