<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar National Convention to Meet Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar National Convention
will meet again after the convention's Convening Commission
completes discussions on basic detailed guidelines regarding
separation of powers between the legislative, executive and
judiciary at different levels, Chief Justice U Aung Toe was quoted
by Tuesday's The New Light of Myanmar as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, no date was set for the re-convening of the
convention.
</P>
<P>
The sessions of the National Convention, which began in January
1993 to lay down fundamental principles for drawing up a new state
constitution, have been in recess for two and a half years since
the last session ended in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
The convention has completed working out detailed principles
for six chapters out of 15 to be included in the new state
constitution. The six chapters are Fundamental Principles,
Structure of the State, Head of State, the Legislature, the
Executive and the Judiciary.
</P>
<P>
U Aung Toe, who is also chairman of the National Convention
Convening Work Committee, said at a recent meeting of the 19th
Work Committee and General Assembly of ASEAN Inter-Parliamentary
Organization held in Kuala Lumpur that Myanmar is making a
step-by-step approach to develop the multi-party democratic
process domestically.
</P>
<P>
The convention has been attended by more than 500 delegates
from eight categories of the delegate groups including political
parties, parliament representatives-elect in the 1990 general
election, national races, peasants, workers, intelligentsia, state
service personnel including the military ones, and invited persons
including turned-in armed groups.
</P>
<P>
In November 1995, all the delegates of the parliament
representatives- elect of the National League for Democracy (NLD)
Party, which won the 1990 general election, withdrew from the
convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increase in Housing Credit Suggested in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to resolve the real
estate crisis, Thai condominium developers have proposed a plan to
the government, suggesting an increase in housing credit, lowering
interest rates as well as increasing level of government land
expropriation.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement from the Thai Condominium Association
available Tuesday, the proposal, aimed at increasing liquidity in
the sector, has been submitted to Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda, who has been tasked with solving the problems in
the real estate sector.
</P>
<P>
The association said in the statement that the government
should find some urgent measures to encourage commercial banks and
financial institutions to extend credit and lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The association suggested that risk weighting ratio for housing
credit fall below 50 percent, commercial banks and financial
institutions be allowed to sell their housing loan portfolios to
the central bank or other institutions at a discount, and banks
sell export credits at a discount to the Export and Import Bank of
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The association said housing credit is at the heart of the real
estate sector problem and a resolution to it would stimulate a
greater spending power in home-buyers, help real estate developers
to improve their liquidity and thus help lower the non-performing
loans of commercial banks and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, boosting the ailing real estate sector would allow a
lot of related businesses, for instance, building materials
producers and retail outlets, construction firms, furniture
manufacturers and retail outlets, electric appliance businesses,
and others to sell their products and services.
</P>
<P>
The improved situation would provide new jobs and reduce the
need for lay-offs, not to mention the increased taxes and fees the
government will be able to collect.
</P>
<P>
The association hoped that improving the country's real estate
and financial sectors would finally act as a driving force for
economic recovery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Seeks 879M Dollars for Post-Flood Rehabilitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has sought 879
million U.S. dollars of foreign assistance for immediate flood
relief and post-flood rehabilitation, The Bangladesh Observer
daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's needs for immediate flood relief are 1.35 million
tons of foodgrain worth 242 million dollars and 112 million
dollars as cash aid, the daily quoted an official of the Economic
Relations Division (ERD) of the Finance Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
The post-flood requirement for rehabilitation has been
estimated at 525 million dollars, he said, adding that the
preliminary estimate of requirement in different sectors has been
sent to all the donor countries and agencies.
</P>
<P>
Since early July when the monsoon season began in the country,
45 of the country's 64 districts have been hit by flood, with
over 20.7 million people affected and the death toll rising to
423, according to the latest figures issued by the Control Room of
the Relief and Disaster Management Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the nearly two-month-long flood has damaged over
227,000 hectares of crops, more than 377,000 houses, 9,347
kilometers of roads, 4,121 kilometers of embankments, 4,652
bridges and culverts and 1,052 educational institutions.
</P>
<P>
The government has appealed to donors for assistance, and got
positive response from them. Donor countries and agencies such as
the United States, Japan, Britain, Canada, Australia, India, the
Netherlands and the Asian Development Bank have provided or agreed
to provide aid to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
