<HEADLINE> Austria Urges Political Settlement of Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Defense Minister
Verner Fasslabend, on a visit to Macedonia Monday, urged the two
conflicting parties in Kosovo to cooperate in finding a political
solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Austria is of the view that there exists the possibility of a
political solution to the Kosovo crisis, Fasslabend said in a
meeting with his Macedonian counterpart, Lazar Kitanovski, in
Skopje, according to news reports from the Macedonian capital.
</P>
<P>
Fasslabend said that a political settlement of the Kosovo
crisis should not lead to the occurrence of another Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, Kitanovski said Macedonia is
trying its best to avoid any involvement in the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The two defense ministers agreed that the Kosovo crisis should
be settled at an early date and that there would be a human
disaster if it could not be solved by this winter.
</P>
<P>
Fasslabend also met with Macedonian Foreign Minister Blagoj
Handziski earlier in the day. The two sides reportedly spoke
highly of the relations between their two countries and exchanged
views on regional security issues.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo is a Yugoslav province where ethnic albanians make up 90
percent of its total population, who have been seeking
independence from Yugoslavia since the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The province was plunged into chaos in February when ethnic
Albanian separatists intensified their campaign for independence.
Although the path for a political settlement of the crisis is not
blocked, the United States has threatened the use of force for a
military solution to it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
