<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Eyes Defense Ministry for Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The cash-strapped Thai
government is considering requiring the Defense Ministry to
contribute a bigger slice of the proceeds from its commercial
radio and television networks to the state's depleted coffers.
</P>
<P>
The Nation newspaper Tuesday quoted Deputy Prime Minister
Bhichai Rattakul as saying that he had suggested Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai to consider allowing the Office of the
Auditor-General to check on the income of army-owned TV Channels 5
and 7 and its more than 200 radio stations nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Other government agencies targeted by the Office of the
Auditor-General as part of the efforts to boost the government's
shaking financial position include the Justice Ministry, which
receives a large income from the interest generated from huge
amounts of cash placed as bonds for bail.
</P>
<P>
Bhichai said the government wants to know how much money the
army-owned television and radio stations are making each year so
as to decide the financial contribution they will be required to
make to the state coffers.
</P>
<P>
The Office of the Auditor-General has never examined income
generated from television and radio stations owned by the army and
other branches of the armed forces because proceeds from these
activities are currently categorized as non-budgetary funds, which
can be spent at their discretion.
</P>
<P>
Media watchers have estimated that army-owned television and
radio stations collectively earn billions of baht in profits each
year.
</P>
<P>
Relevant laws and regulations will have to be amended to
empower the Office of the Auditor-General to examine income from
commercial television and radio stations and allow the Finance
Ministry to require contribution from the proceeds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
