<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republican Leader says Censure Inadequate in Lewinsky Matter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott Monday called President Bill Clinton's behavior with a
former White House intern "disgusting," saying Clinton has reduced
the stature of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Lott also suggested that censure might not be an adequate
congressional response.
</P>
<P>
Lott declined to say whether he thinks Clinton should remain in
office, but he backed away from his suggestion earlier this year
that censuring the president, as opposed to impeachment
proceedings, might be the way to go.
</P>
<P>
"That was March. This is the first of September as of
tomorrow, and a lot has happened since then," The Associated Press
quoted Lott as saying. "... Censure really doesn't do anything.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not, at this point, going to say what is appropriate
either way," he added.
</P>
<P>
A senior Senate Republican aide, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said later that Lott no longer believes censure is
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
"As a husband and father, I am offended by the president's
behavior," Lott told reporters as the Senate returned from its
summer recess.
</P>
<P>
"There is a moral dimension to the American presidency, and
today that dimension, that power, has been lost in scandal and in
deception. As a citizen, I'm disappointed in the way the highest
office in the nation has been reduced in stature and diminished in
credibility."
</P>
<P>
Asked if he would urge Clinton to resign, Lott said he would
await any report Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr is expected to
submit.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know if it will rise to levels that could justify
proceeding in the House on impeachment or anything else. So I am
going to wait for that report and withhold judgment or further
comment until I see it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Later Monday, Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle said Clinton
has told him he plans to comment further on his relationship with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
"I think he will say more," Daschle told CNN. "I think that
will happen." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
