<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Builds Railway Linking Hainan Island With Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- China is now constructing its
first cross-strait railroad that will connect Hainan Island with
the mainland, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the Guangdong-Hainan Railway is
scheduled to be finished in 2001.
</P>
<P>
The 524.6-kilometer railway will include Zhanjiang-Hai'an
Railway in Guangdong Province, ferries from Hai'an to Haikou,
capital of Hainan Province, and the railway which rounds the
western part of Hainan from Haikou to Sanya. It will handle 30
million tons annually when completed.
</P>
<P>
The ferries will be able to withstand winds up to fresh gale.
When completed, the 4.5 billion yuan railway project will connect
with the rest of the country's railway network, thus strengthening
the relationship between the island province and the rest of the
country.
</P>
<P>
It will also advance Hainan's development and provide another
market link for rich marine resources to the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 10th anniversary of the founding of Hainan
Province, also the country's fifth special economic zone after
Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Shantou and Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Huge costs have delayed the project, said an official with the
Ministry of Railways. The project now has financial support from
the Ministry of Railways, and the governments of Guangdong and
Hainan provinces.
</P>
<P>
The complexity of the project and the engineering challenge of
getting tracks across the Qiongzhou Strait also hinders the
construction, said the official, who didn't rule out the
possibility of building tunnels across the nearly 25-km strait to
connect the two provinces.
</P>
<P>
But the construction of undersea tunnels would take longer time
and be more expensive than the ferry system now proposed, said the
official.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the cross-strait railway is the
ninth railway project begun in China this year. The country
planned ten major railway projects this year. The final one is a
trunk railway from Northeast China's Heilongjiang to East China's
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Construction on this year's last railway project, with a length
of 2,000 km, will start this month or October. It will take four
years to complete.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Secret Thai Fund Found in U.S. Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Nation newspaper Monday reported that the huge sum of money
had been stashed away and accumulated over the years and no one
seemed to have been aware of its existence because the Defense
Ministry had failed to report it to the Finance Ministry as
required.
</P>
<P>
The official, who did not give his name, said the Finance
Ministry's Office of the Auditor-General recently came across the
account at the U.S. central bank while inspecting the government's
overseas assets.
</P>
<P>
The Office of the Auditor-General has been instructed to
scrutinize the government's overseas assets as part of the efforts
to improve the government's flagging fiscal position. A huge
shortfall in the government's revenue collection is expected as a
result of the current economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
The account was opened in 1982 under a recommendation of the
Finance Ministry for arms purchase by the Defense Ministry, which
was required to report the balances in the account to the Finance
Ministry every year.
</P>
<P>
Apparently the Defense Ministry had not reported it. The
Defense Ministry could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the existence of the account had been known to few
outside the Defense Ministry until U.S. government officials
recently mentioned it as a possible source of downpayment for
Thailand's planned acquisition of F-18 fighter jets, which was
later scrapped.
</P>
<P>
It is still not clear how the account had eluded the detection
of the Bank of Thailand or the Office of the Auditor-General for
so long. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Venezuela Drops 70 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment in Venezuela
dropped by 70 percent in the first half of this year in comparison
with the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to figures issued Monday by the Promotion Council of
Investments (CONAPRI), investment in the period was only 50.8
million U.S. dollars, compared with 172.35 million dollars in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
CONAPRI attributed the decrease to election times in Latin
America, which generated distrust among foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The fall of crude oil prices, the lack of a profitable activity
to replace the oil business, and the Asian crisis are affecting
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
