<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Raise More Locust-Killing Chickens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region has decided to greatly increase the number
of locust-killing chickens it raises next year.
</P>
<P>
As 100,000 trained chickens and hundreds of thousands of
migrating starlings played a key role in controlling the largest
locust disaster in the last decade, only eight counties around
Urumqi, capital of the region, decided to raise 200,000 trained
chickens next year.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang is often attacked by locusts and more than 150 species
have occurred in the region in recent years.
</P>
<P>
A trained chicken can kill locusts in half a hectare of
grassland during a summer season.
</P>
<P>
A chicken usually needs two months of training before it acts
as a "soldier" to kill the enemy -- locusts.
</P>
<P>
As soon as a herdsman blows his whistle, a trained chicken
begins searching for and eating locusts in the grass.
</P>
<P>
As the locusts contain rich protein, these chickens can be sold
at a much higher price than ordinary chickens in the region.
</P>
<P>
The central and regional government has spent 10 million yuan
(1.2 million U.S. dollars) in curbing the spread of locusts and
this year's locust-caused disaster is now under control.
</P>
<P>
Har Wenguang, head of Xinjiang's locust and rat extermination
office, said starlings, the natural enemy of locusts from the
Indian subcontinent, each May protect 186,000 hectares of
grassland and the trained chickens consume locusts on 4,000
hectares.
</P>
<P>
Har said an adult starling can consume more than 120 locusts
each day.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, Xinjiang has spent more than 140,000
U.S. dollars to build nests to attract migrating starlings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Administration Tries to Reassure Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton Administration
tried to assure investors Monday that the United States economy is
basically sound despite the second biggest points plunge in Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said he had talked to President
Bill Clinton, who was on Air Force One on his way to Moscow for a
summit with Russian leaders, after Monday's stock market closed
with the Dow Jones industrial average down more than 512 points.
</P>
<P>
"The fundamentals of the United States economy are strong due
in part to the sound policies we've been following," Rubin stated.
</P>
<P>
"The prospects for growth, low unemployment and low inflation
continue to be strong," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said he had also spoken to Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan and officials around the world.
</P>
<P>
"The world is currently working its way through a difficult
period," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was particularly important that Japan "move ahead
with actions to put its economy back on track so that it can be a
source of strength for the rest of the world."
</P>
<P>
Payment and settlement systems and other market mechanisms were
working effectively, unlike in 1987, when backlogs occurred and
many small investors were unable to cash out their holdings when
they wanted.
</P>
<P>
There was a "slight" problem on the Chicago Board Options
Exchange (CBOE), but it was resolved and the exchange is expected
to open on time Tuesday, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
CBOE officials said computer systems had to struggle to handle
the trading volume just before the close of trading, resulting in
a temporary slowdown in quotes for stock options on the trading
floor.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also urged the Republicans in Congress to authorize U.S.
additional contributions to the International Monetary Fund (IMF),
which helps support countries in financial trouble.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to receive full IMF funding so that the IMF
will have sufficient resources to respond to crises," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
