<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Historical Sites Under Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's 12,000 documented
sites and monuments of historical value have come under threat,
according to Archaeology Department sources Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Last week five valuable guardstones belonging to the
Medirigiriya historical site in Polonnaruwa in the North Central
province were reportedly plundered.
</P>
<P>
Director General of Archeology Siran Deraniyagala complains
that he has only 40 watchers (security guards) to ensure the
safety of the country's historical treasures, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Deraniyagala was quoted as saying that his department also
covers sites and monuments amounting to another 100,000 over a
land extent of 16,000 acres but he has a staff of only about 1,400
to administer them.
</P>
<P>
The director lamented that out of his staff only 14 were
professionally trained. This was totally inadequate to meet the
demand within the department.
</P>
<P>
As a means of remedying this situation, the department has
already launched a program in the North Western province of
inventorying such sites. There is a grave necessity for the
private sector to come in to the functions of the department of
protecting and conserving historical sites and monuments, the
sources pointed out.
</P>
<P>
On the question of the increased threats to these sites from
treasure hunters and other vandals, the sources added that the
public must be conscious of the need to preserve their cultural
heritage and not leave that task to his department alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
