<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Victims Still Living Peaceful Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Along the Yangtze River running
through Wuhan, capital of central China's Hubei Province, and in
the suburban areas, more than 277,000 troops and residents are
keeping their eyes open on the ravaging flood waters, with
vehicles and sandbags nearby to tackle any possible dangers.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily reported that the streets in the downtown
section of the city are hustle and bustle as usual, schools
prepare for their new semester, peddlers yell at the market, and
cabs shuttle their customers.
</P>
<P>
Yun Lihua, 65, has kept her store open near the Longwangmiao
ferry on the Riverside Road in Jianghan District since the
anti-flood fight began in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
Located at the junction of the Hanjiang and Yangtze rivers, the
1,080-meter-long ferry, dubbed as "Dragon King's Temple" in
Chinese, in one of the most vulnerable sections on the Yangtze
dyke.
</P>
<P>
"I reckon that the water will not flow in the city," Yun said
yesterday, pointing at the ferry which is less than 150 meters
away. "The soldiers and the district officials have been stationed
there for more than 60 days. I needn't worry about any risks."
</P>
<P>
In Fanhu Town, Jiangxia District in southwest Wuhan, more than
100 farmers from Chijishan Village gathered on Saturday under the
hot sun to receive their share of disaster relief from the city's
Civil Affairs Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Shili, whose two hectares of land was engulfed by the
flood, got 1,210 yuan (146 US dollars) that day. He had been
granted aid from the bureau twice before, while Chen Yongquan, the
village chief, was only given 40.9 yuan, because his loss was
slight.
</P>
<P>
"Based on meticulous checks and calculation, the city's Civil
Affairs Bureau and various instances at the county's level have so
far sent 19.6 million yuan (2.3 million US dollars) and 23 million
yuan (2.7 million US dollars) worth of material to the victims in
the city's flood-hit areas," said Lin Xiaoqun, an official with
the Wuhan Bureau of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Luo Yousong, director of the Wuhan Education Commission, said
that students whose schools were destroyed by the floods had all
been given a special pass, enabling them to enter nearby schools
without change.
</P>
<P>
He said no student will be left out of school because of the
floods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
