<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Ministers Ridiculed on Internet by Hackers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard and his key ministers suffered unexpected negative
publicity as they were ridiculed on the Internet by hackers
Monday, the first day of Australia's federal election campaign.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph reported that the prime minister, instead
of being referred to as "The Honorable John Howard MP", had become
"The Dishonorable John Howard MP: Prime Minister for Pain,
Suffering and Inequity" on the Liberal Party's site.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the prime minister Tuesday confirmed the
report, saying the web site for the Australian Liberal Party,
whose leader is John Howard, was vandalized Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
The site closed soon after the attack was discovered and the
offending material was then removed, the spokesman told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Treasurer Peter Costello, the would-be successor to John Howard
as leader of the party, Australian Foreign Minister Alexander
Downer and Workplace Relations Minister Peter Reith also suffered
ridicule on their web sites.
</P>
<P>
The treasurer, who was behind the sweeping taxation reform plan
unveiled last month, became "Minister for the Rich, Stomping the
Poor and Wrecking the Economy".
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister was called "Minister for Foreign
Humiliation" on his web site, which was also linked to
Disneyland.com.
</P>
<P>
Workplace Relations Minister Peter Reith, who has launched a
nationwide campaign to break the monopoly of the nation's trade
union over seaports, became "Minister for Destruction of Workplace
Fairness, the Gestapo and Propaganda" with his site linked to the
Maritime Union of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Overnight repairs to the Liberal Party's Internet site have
restored dignity to Prime Minister John Howard.
</P>
<P>
But early Tuesday morning the sites of some key ministers were
still unable to be accessed, including those of Reith, Environment
Minister Robert Hill, Social Security Minister Jocelyn Newman,
Resources Minister Warwick Parer, Justice Minister Amanda Vanstone
and Attorney-General Daryl Williams.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the Australian Federal Police declined to say
whether the police were going to investigate the case, adding they
would consider taking action after receiving a complaint from the
Australian Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
About one million Australian homes were now hooked up to the
Internet, the Australian Bureau of Statistics said last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Australia's major political parties and government
organizations have their web sites established on the Internet and
are trying to use the net to get their message across to voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
