<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 100-year-old Bronze Gun Unearthed in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, Septmeber 1 (Xinhua) -- A bronze gun made at least
100 years ago has been unearthed at a construction site for a
secondary school in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The gun was made during the late Qing Dynasty (1644-1911). It
is 1.6 meters long and weighs 250 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Local archeologists said the 70 millimeter gun was well
preserved, and characters carved on its body, which still could be
seen clearly, listed the names of craftsmen and officials who
supervised its manufacture.
</P>
<P>
Several iron guns were discovered in the region,
archeologists said, but this is the first time a bronze gun has
been unearthed. The discovery should benefit the study of arms
manufacturing during the Qing Dynasty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian House Speaker Agrees to Limit Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian House Speaker
Harmoko Monday agreed to demands that the incumbent and future
presidents should only be allowed to serve a maximum of two
five-year terms.
</P>
<P>
"If the number of presidential terms is not limited, it would
accelerate the centralization of power," Harmoko told a plenary
meeting of the House of Representatives Monday here.
</P>
<P>
Such action will uphold the sovereignty of people, he said,
adding that Indonesians no longer want long-serving presidents.
</P>
<P>
"Our experience as a nation for 53 years is more than enough.
We have enough lessons to avoid any kind of state management that
is not in line with the values of democracy, justice and welfare,"
Harmoko was quoted by national newspapers Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the past, he said, the power of the government tended to
become absolute and authoritarian especially when the executive
ignored criticism, suggestions and supervision from the
legislature, social institutions and other supervisory agencies.
</P>
<P>
"So, we see the upcoming People's Consultative Assembly (MPR)
special session as crucial, since it will become a beginning for
more fundamental reform by the poll-produced MPR," Harmoko said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's highest legislative body, the MPR, is scheduled to
hold a four-day special session on November 10. One of the main
items on the agenda will be to reset the election date from 2002
to 1999.
</P>
<P>
With the revisions, Indonesia would not only see an earlier
election, but also "change more quickly the existing political
system so it can become more acceptable to the people," Harmoko
said.
</P>
<P>
He believed the elections, scheduled for between May and June
next year, could be a new beginning for the nation in handling the
problems it was currently facing.
</P>
<P>
"Through the general session of the MPR established after the
poll, we could even lay the groundwork for a national life that
reflects more the spirit of the people's sovereignty, in which we
will also see a limited presidential term," he added.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the MPR Working Body, who are now preparing for the
special session, told reporters Monday that the special session
will discuss a wide range of issues.
</P>
<P>
Most issues raised by legislators were prompted by the public's
demand for sweeping reforms, Deputy Chairman of the MPR Working
body Ahmad Roestandi said.
</P>
<P>
The issues include limiting the presidential term, assessing
the accountability of former president Soeharto, and revoking a
decree that gives the president absolute power in times of
emergency, Roestandi added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
