<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Rejects Presidential Re-election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 31 (Xinhua) -- An overwhelming majority of
Panamanian voters said "no" to a proposed constitutional reform
that would allow presidents to seek a successive term, according
to the latest results of Sunday's referendum.
</P>
<P>
The Board of Elections said that with 98.6 percent of the 4,478
polling booths reporting, 63.7 percent of the votes were against
the reform while 34.3 percent were in favor.
</P>
<P>
Of the nation's 1,718,870 eligible voters, 64 percent went to
Sunday's poll, compared with a 40-percent turnout in the 1992
referendum on the dissolution of the National Defense.
</P>
<P>
Colon Province, characterized by a soaring jobless rate and
rumblings that President Ernesto Perez Balladares had not kept his
campaign promise to help the poor, shouted the loudest "no" voice.
</P>
<P>
The country's next presidential election is in May.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the referendum marked a firm step forward in
Panama's democracy process, following the 1992 referendum and 1994
general elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Banks Opened to Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
treat foreign investors equally with local investors in the
opportunity to acquire ailing local banks, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"We will invite foreign investors to participate in the
restructuring of our banks," Minister of Finance Bambang Subianto
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said participation of overseas investors in the
restructuring of the troubled banking sector was essential because
of the substantial funding required to clear up its problems,
local leading newspapers reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bambang said the amount of money to recapitalize the ailing
banks would be large because the level of non-performing loans was
estimated to reach 50 percent of more than 600 trillion rupiah
(54.5 billion U.S. dollars) in outstanding loans, equivalent to
more than 40 percent of the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The government was revising the country's banking law to
abolish the foreign ownership limitation for local banks,
currently set at 49 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the finance minister submitted proposed amendments
to the 1992 Banking Act at a plenary session of the House of
Representatives, demanding foreign investors be allowed to own 100
percent shares in national banks.
</P>
<P>
The government recently suspended the operation of three banks
and took over the share-holding of four others in its first major
efforts to rehabilitate the sector.
</P>
<P>
The seven banks had received Bank Indonesia (central bank)
liquidity support equivalent to more than 500 percent of their
capital. They are believed to have channeled 70 to 100 percent of
the funds to affiliated business groups.
</P>
<P>
In November last year, the government closed 16 insolvent
private banks under an agreement with the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) for economic and financial reform. In April this year,
the government again suspended the operation of seven private
banks and merged three others.
</P>
<P>
Economists held the ailing banking system is one of the major
causes for the prolonged economic crisis in Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
