<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brief Economic News From Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries occurring in the
past few days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Exports in Argentina are expected to decrease
following the global financial crises, the Chamber of Exporters
predicted.
</P>
<P>
The chamber blames the situation on the inability of Argentine
goods to compete because of the revaluation of the peso.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The Interamerican Bank of Development will give
Nicaragua a 740-million-dollar loan to strengthen its economic and
social sectors.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the loans made by BID will be
used to help public banks consolidate financial systems.
</P>
<P>
It will also be used to support the reform and modernization of
the National Power System, as well as Health and Education sectors.
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- Peru's current deficit in the balance of payments has
reached 2.21 billion dollars in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
This amount represents a 60 percent increase compared to the
same period in 1997, which was 1.381 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico's crude oil price was 10.14 dollars per
barrel in July, a 1.5 percent increase over June, the Estatal de
Petroleos Mexicanos (Mexican State Owned Company) PEMEX said.
</P>
<P>
The company said that the average price of crude oil has
dropped. The price has gone from 11.82 dollars at the beginning
of the year to 9,67 dollars per barrel in March, the lowest price
so far.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's bus production has reached 15,072 units in
the first six months of this year, compared with 11,589 units in
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian National Association of Car Producers predicted
that the Brazilian production of buses this year could exceed
23,000 units, a 6 percent increase over last year, when it stood
at 21,595 units. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980901.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Builds 90 Dams in Past Ten Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has claimed that it has
built 90 dams in the country without any foreign assistance since
the Tatmadaw (Armed Forces) took over the state power in late
1988.
</P>
<P>
The claim was made by Lieutenant General Tin Oo, second
secretary of the Myanmar State Peace and Development Council, at
Monday's opening ceremony of a latest dam, the Pin Creek dam, in
central Mandalay division, The New Light of Myanmar newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The completed 90 dams irrigate nearly 546,750 hectares of
farmland, he said, urging the people to help maintain the
facilities till future generations and to use water efficiently.
</P>
<P>
Of the 90 dams, 22 are in central Mandalay division where arid
zones lie.
</P>
<P>
Tin Oo disclosed that the project for reforestation and
betterment of weather conditions of the central arid region has
been extended from 8 districts to 13 districts.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that priority is being given to greening and
forest restoration of the Popa mountain region, the main watershed
of central Myanmar which is related to the reforestation of the
arid region.
</P>
<P>
He warned against indiscriminate felling of trees and
destruction of forests which will cause severe weather changes.
</P>
<P>
He called for forest conservation and increased building of
dams to help put more land under crops in the central part of the
country and green the region.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar registered a 4.6 percent growth of its gross domestic
product (GDP) in 1997-98 fiscal year ending in March, in which
agriculture, the mainstay of the country's economy, grew by 2.9
percent in output value, accounting for 35.6 percent of the total
GDP and about 35 percent of the export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
