<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, September 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin Monday renominated
Viktor Chernomyrdin as the country's prime minister, hours after
the nomination was rejected by the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Only 94 deputies voted for Chernomyrdin, way below the required
226 votes from 450 lawmakers of the State Duma. Of the 345
deputies who cast votes 251 voted against, with no abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The vote, originally scheduled for 18:00 local time (1400 GMT),
was taken one hour later to allow deputies to vent, for the most
part, their anger at the government and President Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Zyuganov, leader of the Communist Party, the largest
opposition faction with 133 of the 450 seats, said Chernomyrdin
"does not possess a single quality necessary for leading the
government."
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov blasted the government's performance in the past seven
years, both under Chernomyrdin from 1992 until March this year,
and under Sergei Kiriyenko, who was dismissed abruptly on August
23. (Russia-Premier-Yeltsin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain's Labor government is considering to call a
meeting of the Group of Seven (G7) industrial nations to discuss
the worsening Russian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman was quoted by Reuters as saying here
Monday, "The possibility of a meeting in some form of G7 leaders
is being actively considered."
</P>
<P>
"There'll be a decision in the next few days, once we know the
shape of the new government in Russia... we need to know who we're
dealing with," he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past weekend, British Prime Minister Tony Blair, whose
country is the current G7 president, held a series of telephone
discussions with other G7 leaders to exchange views on the Russian
situation. (UK-Russia-G7 Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- The Cambodian Constitutional Council rejected
opposition parties' poll complaints Monday, saying the complaints
were "baseless."
</P>
<P>
The rejection by the nation's highest legislative body paved
the way for the National Election Committee (NEC) to announce the
official election results.
</P>
<P>
The two main opposition parties -- the royalist FUNCINPEC party
led by Prince Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) of former
finance minister Sam Rainsy -- lodged 110 complaints to the
Constitutional Council.
</P>
<P>
Among the 17 complaints accepted by the council, two were put
to hearing Monday while the 15 others were ruled out.
(Cambodia-Election Complaint)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The United States and the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) resumed talks on nuclear matters in New
York on Monday after they adjourned last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said the talks, which began on August 21 and
have had three sessions, resumed this afternoon at the U.S.
Mission to the United Nations, with the U.S. side led by Deputy
Assistant Secretary of State Charles Kartman and the DPRK
represented by Vice Foreign Minister Kim Gye-kwan.
</P>
<P>
Like in previous sessions, both sides did not give any
information about what they talked about.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials only confirmed last week that the 1994 Agreed
Framework for the DPRK to freeze its own nuclear program in
exchange for two western-built light-water reactors was on the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
The meeting today took place hours after western media reported
that Pyongyang allegedly launched a long-range ballistic missile
over Japan on Monday. (US-DPRK-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton left here Monday for
Moscow, where he is to meet Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Clinton departed Andrews Air Force Base near Washington at 3:10
p.m. local time by Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
As both Clinton and Yeltsin have been wounded at home, analysts
believe that nothing substantial could be achieved during their
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The reason I'm going to Russia," Clinton said shortly before
leaving, "is because we have learned the hard way that problems
that develop beyond our borders sooner or later find their way to
our doorstep unless we help our friends and our neighbors."
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Yeltsin are to meet Tuesday and Wednesday for their
first full-scale summit since March 1997. Since then, they have
met briefly a few times, most recently in May, when both were in
Birmingham, England.
</P>
<P>
The two will focus on security and Russia's economic crisis.
(Clinton-Russia-Summit) 
</P>
</TEXT>
