<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sprewell Refiles Lawsuit Against NBA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Former Golden State Warriors
guard Latrell Sprewell today announced plans to refile a lawsuit
against the team and the NBA, a liitle more than a month after
the case was thrown out of court.
</P>
<P>
Going against the recommendation of the judge who dismissed
the original lawsuit on July 30, Sprewell said he is reviving the
matter to repair his damaged image and because the team and the
NBA acted improperly after a December 1 incident at practice in
which he choked Warriors coach P.J. Carlesimo.
</P>
<P>
"People have this perception of me being this evil person,
this bad person, because they don't have all the facts," said
Sprewell at a news conference in San Francisco. "If I go through
with the lawsuit, they will find out the wrongness that was done."
</P>
<P>
Sprewell also accused the NBA of shredding crucial documents
in the investigation of the matter and denied attacking Carlesimo
a second time, which the Warriors and the league contend.
</P>
<P>
The 30 million U.S. dollars lawsuit was dismissed in
U.S.District Court for Northern California by Judge Vaughn
Walker, who ruled that the case could be revived but recommended
that it be dropped.
</P>
<P>
According to attorneys for Sprewell, the new lawsuit was filed
in the same court but for unspecified damages. The lawsuit seeks
to cap the penalty for his attack on Carlesimo at 1 million
U.S.dollars, the cost in salary of his original 10-game
suspension.
</P>
<P>
"The contract with the players' union clearly states that
either the team or the league can punish me, but not both,"
Sprewell said.
</P>
<P>
Sprewell, a three-time All-Star, was originally suspended for
10 games by the Warriors. Warriors management then terminated the
two-plus years and 23.7 million of his contract. The following
day,the NBA suspended Sprewell for one year, the longest non-drug
ban in league history.
</P>
<P>
The NBA Players Association, which strongly backed Sprewell in
his initial grievances against the league, has not endorsed the
lawsuit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
