<HEADLINE> Prediction of Huge Wellington Quake Reaffirmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A huge earthquake in the
Wellington region is again predicted after new analysis shows
growing tension between the Pacific and Australian tectonic
plates.
</P>
<P>
According to Tuesday's Dominion, a Wellington-based newspaper,
a study conducted jointly by the Geological and Nuclear Sciences
Institute of New Zealand and Massey University has found that
pressure under Wellington potentially makes its fault the most
dangerous of several in the region, including several newly
identified faults.
</P>
<P>
The research coincides with a paper published last month in the
Civil Defense Ministry's Journal Tephra. In the paper,
seismologists Martin Reyners and John Beavan wrote that
sophisticated satellite-measurements of tectonic plate movements
under the southern North Island of New Zealand showed significant
land deformations pointing to the inevitability of big
earthquakes. They made a prediction of big earthquakes in the
region, as well as in more southern regions that are subjected to
strains under the Southern Alps along the west coast of the
country's South Island.
</P>
<P>
The research carried out by the Geological and Nuclear Sciences
Institute and Massey University said that though no one can
predict when, the likely size of a quake out of the big Wellington
fault would be more than 7.6 on the Richter scale. "It could be
greater than 8, if it erupts out of the Wairarapa fault," the
research predicted.
</P>
<P>
The institute study shows five "new" and active faults have
been discovered in the Wellington region during the past five
years, each with the potential to be the source of the big quake.
</P>
<P>
Three of the faults are in the western Tararua Range between
Paraparaumu and Palmerston North; one through Whiteman's Valley
between Wainuiomata and Upper Hutt; and another directly
underneath Martinborough.
</P>
<P>
Another fault, the subduction thrust under Wellington between
the Pacific and Australian plates, is not newly discovered, but is
the subject of new data indicating greater strain.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, with Wellington Regional Council,
the institute has prepared a series of maps analyzing in detail
earthquake risk within individual suburbs and areas. The maps
indicate the dangers from ground shaking, fault movement,
liquefaction, slips, and tsunamis.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion quoted institute geologist Russ Van Dissen as
saying that during the past five or six years there has been a
growing awareness by local authorities of the inevitability of a
big earthquake, and necessary work to mitigate the effects of a
big quake is being carried out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
