<HEADLINE> Clinton Orders Official to Mediate Northwest Pilot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has ordered Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater to mediate with
Northwest Airlines officials and pilot union leaders to resume
negotiations to end the ongoing strike.
</P>
<P>
In his first move toward intervening in the strike, Clinton on
Monday issued a statement from Air Force One en route from
Washington to Moscow saying he had asked Northwest and its pilots
to "redouble their efforts to resolve their differences."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said senior administration officials were in contact
with both parties, "but it is up to the negotiating parties to
reach an agreement."
</P>
<P>
The president said he hoped that an agreement would be
concluded soon in their interests and the interest of the American
people.
</P>
<P>
The strike entered its third day Monday with little sign of
movement toward resolution. The union and the airline said they
were ready to start talks again, but there was no schedule
announced.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, White House officials had said that if the strike
reached Labor Day, September 7, Clinton might reconsider his
decision not to order a 60-day "cooling-off" period for the
parties as he did last year in the early stages of a strike by
American Airlines pilots.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the airlines extended its cancellations of its 1,700
daily flights through Wednesday, and international flights from
Europe also were canceled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Northwest and its pilots' union are arguing over issues of job
security and compensation. Northwest said its last offer would
have paid the average pilot 150,000 U.S. dollars by the end of the
contract in 2002, more than other big airlines.
</P>
<P>
But the 6,100 pilots argued that Northwest misrepresented the
value of the offer, noting that pilots at other airlines are
likely to have new contracts by then. The pilots said their
average salary now is 120,000 dollars per year, but Northwest said
it is 133,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Northwest is the sixth largest airline in number of passengers
carried annually and the fourth-largest in revenue in the United
States. It carries nearly 150,000 passengers a day and 1,315 tons
of cargo on 1,600 flights in North America, Europe and Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
