<HEADLINE> European Bourses Fail in Rallies to Fall with Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets struggled
for most of the day on Monday against the Russian crisis, with
volatile trade ending in losses on the back of a sharp fall on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, after a strong start, the leading DAX index fell
back in line with other world markets, as the Russian political
crisis reached a stalemate over the formation of a new government
with acting prime minister Viktor Chernomyrdin rejected by
parliament as the new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said there was still some strength in corporate
earnings but there is some risk that the DAX will fall back to
4500 points because there are no support levels between 5,000 and
4,500.
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt's electronically-traded Xetra Dax index ended down
114.52 points, or 2.3 percent, at 4,811.28 points.
</P>
<P>
The floor-traded Dax, which closes half an hour before Xetra
dealings, fell even further as it had to catch up with late
electronic losses on Friday and ended down 159.65 points or 3.2
percent at 4,833.89.
</P>
<P>
The markets drew early limited comfort from a 1.38 percent
rally in Tokyo stocks, though elsewhere in Asia most share markets
took a tumble, led by a seven percent dive in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
But an opening plunge on Wall Street contributed to the late
pall over European share trade, while the absence of London,
Europe's largest bourse, for a market holiday was considered a
dampening influence, too.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French shares were volatile, too, falling over 2
percent at one stage on a choppy futures and options expiry
although prices picked up later.
</P>
<P>
The leading index, the Cac 40, ended 1.5 percent down at
3,651.85 points after being up a similar amount at the start of
the session.
</P>
<P>
Many investors were sidelined by the Russia crisis, although
current prices were good value with interest rates falling and
fundamentals still solid, brokers say.
</P>
<P>
The story was similar elsewhere with Spain's IBEX share index
down 1.4 percent, while the Swiss Market index shed 1.6 percent
and Amsterdam's AEX index was down 0.6 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
