<HEADLINE> US West Employees Begin Returning Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Some 34,000 U.S. West
employees began to return to work Monday following a tentative
settlement that involves wage increase and limits on mandatory
overtime work in a new three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
The tentative agreement contains a wage hike of 10.9 percent
over three years, a 21 percent increase in pension benefits and a
500 U.S. dollars contract ratification bonus.
</P>
<P>
It is in line with agreements the Communications Workers of
America has reached with other regional Baby Bell companies, the
union said.
</P>
<P>
Union officials expected that the agreement would be ratified
by 60 percent to 70 percent of union members.
</P>
<P>
The strike began August 16. In the 15-day strike, the first in
the company's 14-year history, operators, technicians and customer
service representatives walked off the job in 13 states. It forced
customers to wait for phone repairs and installations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
