<HEADLINE> Security Council Calls for Peaceful Solution in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Monday adopted a presidential statement, calling for a peaceful
solution to the conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Danilo Turk, president of the 15-member council, said that the
peaceful solution included an immediate ceasefire, the withdrawal
of all foreign forces and the initiation of a peaceful process of
political dialogue with a view to achieving national
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The statement also reaffirmed the need for all states in the
region to "refrain from any interference in each other's internal
affairs," and voiced its "support for all the regional diplomatic
initiatives aimed at a peaceful settlement of the conflict."
</P>
<P>
"The problem of the Democratic Republic of Congo must be solved
on the basis of a process of all-inclusive national reconciliation
which fully respects the equality and harmony of all ethnic groups
and which leads to the holding of democratic, free and fair
elections as soon as possible," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement also condemned "reported summary
executions, torture, harassment and detention of civilians based
on their ethnic origin, the recruitment and use of child
soldiers, the killing or wounding of combatants who have laid
down their weapons."
</P>
<P>
"In particular, the Council calls for the protection of the
civilian population" in the country, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The presidential statement came as African countries are
striving for a negotiated solution to the multi-lateral conflict
raging in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
The fighting broke out on August 2 when ethnic Tutsis in
eastern Congo rebelled against President Laurent Kabila, who has
remained in power for about 15 months. Kabila accused neighboring
Uganda and Rwanda of arming and backing the rebellion, a charge
that both governments deny.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Secretary-General of
the Organization of African Unity Salim Ahmed Salim would join
central and southern African leaders at the upcoming Non-aligned
Movement summit for parallel talks on the Congo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
