<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First-Ever Verdict on Crime of Genocide due September 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations tribunal
will hand down on September 2 the first-ever verdict on the crime
of genocide by an international court, U.N. Department of Public
Information said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It also said two days later, the Tribunal, the International
Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda, based in Arusha, Tanzania, will
pronounce in a separate case, the first-ever sentenced for
genocide, the release said.
</P>
<P>
These two landmark decisions will also for the first time bring
to practical life, the lofty ideals of the Genocide Convention.
</P>
<P>
Through the Tribunal, the Convention has been lifted from
statute books to become, 50 years after its adoption in the wake
of the holocaust, a testament to the world's renewed determination
to collectively tackle genocide in a manner it never has before.
</P>
<P>
The Rwanda Tribunal was created by the United Nations Security
Council in November 1994 after one of the most intense periods of
mass exterminations in human history. At least 500,000 people,
primarily Tutsis and moderate Hutus, were brutally massacred in
just three months of that year.
</P>
<P>
In the dock now are Jean-Paul Akayeau, who was the mayor of
Taba district and whose verdict will be pronounced on September 2,
and more significantly, Jean kambanda, who was Rwanda's Prime
Minister during the genocide, has pleaded guilty. His sentence
will be announced in September 4.
</P>
<P>
The Tribunal has in its custody a total of 26 indicated
Rwandans and 5 suspects. All 31 come from rwanda's governing elite
during the time the genocide took place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
